<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Vice President to Visit Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States Vice
President Albert Al Gore is due in Saudi Arabia Friday for a
two-day visit, U.S. diplomatic sources in Saudi capital Riyadh
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency quoted the sources as saying that Gore
would meet Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdullah
Ibn Abdul-Aziz, discussing the U.S.-led efforts in reviving the
Mideast peace process and ways to promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Gore would voice to Saudi leaders Washington's
keenness in advancing the Mideast peace process and breaking the
current deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross failed to persuade
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to accept a
U.S. initiative aimed at reviving the peace process during his
recent visit to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal calls on Israel to hand back to the
Palestinians 13.1 percent more of the West Bank in its second
troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But Israel insists on handing back no more than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gore's visit comes ahead of the May 4 London meeting during
which U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will meet
Netanyahu, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in an effort to break
the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the first leg on Gore's three-nation Mideast
tour, which also includes stops in Israel and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government has been urging the U.S. administration
to make its utmost efforts to break the deadlock in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Gore's last visit to Saudi Arabia was in March 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
