<HEADLINE> UK Rejects Demands for More POW Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The British government Wednesday
ruled out the possibility of demanding more Japanese compensation
for surviving prisoners of war (POW) camps during the Second World
War.
</P>
<P>
Some of the British surviving veterans have insisted that the
1951 peace treaty must be reopened so that they can receive more
cash payments from the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a parliamentary debate on the issue Wednesday
afternoon, British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett said
that in 1955 the British government had already studied the case
for challenging a 1951 treaty under which Japan paid small sums of
money to camp survivors.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said, "The preliminary legal advice that I have
received is that it is not in fact now open to the government to
reopen the provisions of the peace treaty on this basis."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the British government in 1955 had closed its
options by deciding not to reopen the British agreement with the
Japanese on the basis of the Swiss accord.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said in an
interview on the Internet that it was important that this dispute
should not damage Britain's harmonious relations with Japan.
</P>
<P>
"I understand how people might feel about this but it is
important to recognize that our relationship with Japan, which is
an extremely important one, must look forward as well as back."
</P>
</TEXT>
