<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Concerned at Nigerian Sentences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Pretoria Wednesday
expressed its concern over the sentencing of 26 Nigerian military
officers and civilians found guilty by a military tribunal for
plotting a coup against the Nigerian military government.
</P>
<P>
The verdict handed down Tuesday included six death sentences,
among them the former chief of general staff, Oladipo Diya, and
two former cabinet ministers, Abdulkareem Adisa and Tajudeen
Olanrewaju, who allegedly plotted to overthrow the military
regime of Sani Abacha in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Department said in a statement Wednesday
that the South African government "strongly urge the Nigerian
military government to refrain from carrying out the six death
sentences handed down."
</P>
<P>
The South African government had noted that the trial had not
taken place in an open court, and that the defendants had been
represented by military lawyers, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The special military tribunal was required to submit the
sentences to the provisional ruling council for confirmation. If
they were confirmed, the accused could be executed by firing
squad.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also called on the Abacha government to consider
the effects on Nigeria "at this critical juncture in its
history."
</P>
<P>
It warned of a likely "adverse reaction, both inside Nigeria
and internationally," which would have impact on all levels of
Nigerian society and its interaction with the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Abacha has been nominated as the only candidate in Nigeria's
presidential elections set for August 1. The absence of even a
token opposition candidate has prompted international criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
