<HEADLINE> World's Largest Peony Cultivation Base Plans Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Heze City in east China's Shandong
Province, already the world's largest peony growing base, plans to
further increase its peony growing area from the current 2,000
ha to 3,300 ha by the year 2000, according to Mayor Wang Hao.
</P>
<P>
Heze's peony output accounts for more than 80 percent of
the country's total, with annual sales of nearly one million
flowers, the mayor said, noting that the city exports peonies
to more than 30 countries, including Japan, the United States, the
UK, the Netherlands and Germany.
</P>
<P>
He said that Heze will give full play to its peony resources
and is carrying out multi-purpose utilization of the flower.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment is welcome, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Peony cultivation in the area dates back more than 600 years.
During the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) its peony cultivation fields
reached 33 ha, and peony flowers sold well as far as to Guangzhou,
Tianjin and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Heze will hold its seventh peony festival May 22-28, hoping to
attract investment for the industry from both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Heze is also known as the historical setting for the classical
novel, Outlaws of the Marsh.
</P>
<P>
China has three major peony-cultivation bases; the other two
are Luoyang City in central China's Henan Province and Taiyuan,
capital of north China's Shanxi Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
