<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Fall in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. new home sales
plunged 5 percent in March, following healthy growth in the
previous two months of this year, the Commerce Department said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Even with the March drop, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 828,000 homes, sales for the first three months of the year
looked healthy.
</P>
<P>
They were 3.8 percent higher than the corresponding period of
1997, and 1997's total for the full year, 804,000, was a 19-year
high.
</P>
<P>
The fair strong sales have been attributed to low mortgage
rates, which make monthly payments more affordable, and strong
income growth. Sales got an extra boost in January and February
from unseasonably mild weather.
</P>
<P>
February's sales rate, 872,000, was revised down from an
initial estimate of a record 893,000.
</P>
<P>
Despite the new home sales decrease in March, existing home
resales set a record, rising 2.5 percent to a rate of 4.77
million, the National Association of Realtors said earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
By region, new home sales fell 5.1 percent in the South to a
rate of 334,000, lowest in 17 months. They dipped 7.9 percent in
the West to a rate of 222,000 and 4.1 percent in the Midwest to
185,000. But they were unchanged in the Northeast, at 87,000.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the decline in sales allowed an increase in the
inventory of unsold homes to a 4.3-months supply. That's up from a
record-matching low of 3.9 months in February.
</P>
<P>
The median price of a new home was 153,900 dollars in March, up
4 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
