<HEADLINE> Turkish Military Aircraft Violate Cyprus Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish military aircraft
violated Wednesday morning the Nicosia Flight Information Region
(FIR) and Cyprus' airspace on two separate occasions, Cyprus
News Agency (CNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
CNA quoted National Guard sources as saying that two Turkish
F-16 military aircraft entered the Nicosia FIR for about 30
minutes, in violation of International Civil Aviation Organization
(ICAO) regulations.
</P>
<P>
A few hours later, two turkish reconnaissance RF-4 aircraft
violated Cyprus' airspace and flew from the west to the east of
the island's Turkish-occupied northern part for about 25 minutes,
the same sources said.
</P>
<P>
The violations took place during the two Turkish military
exercises code-named "Taurus 1/98" and "Determination 1/98" that
got underway on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish army in Cyprus is participating in the Turkish
navy and airforce exercises, between April 28-30.
</P>
<P>
The exercises are conducted in northern Cyprus and Eastern
Mediterranean international waters and airspace.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops on the island and took over the northern third in the
aftermath of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", where Turkey maintains a
40,000-strong military force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
