<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Patients Sue Doctors in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- More and more British patients are
suing their doctors nowadays for compensation, according to
figures released by the Medical Defense Union (MDU) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The MDU, which represents approximately 80,000 doctors in
Britain, said in its annual report that there has been a 15
percent rise in the number of legal actions brought by patients
against doctors in 1997 over the previous year and a similar
increase in the value of compensation payouts.
</P>
<P>
The most common claims against doctors are for the prescription
of wrong drugs, failure to diagnose a medical condition and
problems relating to pregnancy and labor.
</P>
<P>
Julia Neild, head of the claims handling department at the MDU,
said the figures reflect the general increase in legal actions
against the medical profession since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
"There is no evidence of a fall in standards but with the
introduction of various charters, people's expectations are much
greater," she said.
</P>
<P>
She also warned that if plans to introduce a "no win, no fee"
legal system for medical negligence claims go ahead, there may
well be an increase in litigation against doctors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Producer Inflation at 28-Year Low in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's production
price index fell 0.2 percentage points to 2.3 percent in March,
the lowest level in 28 years, the central statistical service
(CSS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The index hit the 2.1 percent level in May, 1970.
</P>
<P>
The decline of the index, a major precursor of consumer
inflation trend, was largely due to decreases in prices of
petroleum products, electricity and mining and quarrying
products, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Decreases in these prices were counteracted by increases in
the prices of food, textiles and chemical products, resulting in
a monthly decrease of 0.1 percent, the CSS said.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted index increased by 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of increase in the producer price index for
locally produced commodities was 3.3 percent in March, compared
with the corresponding annual rate of 3.6 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the price index for imported goods reflected an
annual decrease of 1.9 percent compared with the corresponding
annual rate of -2.3 percent in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
