<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak-Gore Meetings to Propel Ties, Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President AL Gore will
arrive in Cairo next week for talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak to add a fresh impetus to bilateral ties and the Mideast
peace-making, an Egyptian diplomat said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gore will get acquainted with Egypt's evaluation of the current
Mideast situation in advance of the May 4 London meetings of
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
Egypt's Ambassador to the U.S. Ahmed Maher was quoted by the
Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of views aimed at rescuing the dwindling peace
process also comes after the talks Mubarak held Tuesday in Cairo
with Netanyahu and U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Near
East Affairs Martin Indyk, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cairo became a venue of contacts in the past few days for various
parties working to revive the peace process which has been stalled
since March 1997 over Israeli settlement buildings in Arab East
Jerusalem and long-delayed redeployment from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has so far failed to persuade Israel to give in to a
13.1 percent withdrawal plan after the Palestinians have endorsed it.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the peace-making, Egyptian and American officials
expect the Mubarak-Gore meetings to invigorate economic relations
and the four sub-committees of the Egyptian-American Presidential
Council which "move at a slow pace and need a push."
</P>
<P>
The two-day meetings will tackle all facets of bilateral
relations, especially the development of the U.S.-Egyptian
partnership program, Maher said.
</P>
<P>
The meetings of both delegations will focus on means of
encouraging American investments in Egypt and facilitating the
entry of Egyptian exports into the U.S, he added.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said two agreements will be signed on the
sidelines of the meetings to promote cooperation in environment
and the medium and small industries.
</P>
<P>
Gore will be accompanied by a delegation grouping the assistant
secretary of state for economic affairs, the deputy assistant
secretary of trade, deputy secretary of state for economic affairs
and the deputy director of the American International Development
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Gore's visit falls within the context of a regional tour that
includes Saudi Arabia and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
