<HEADLINE> Saddam Chairs Joint Meeting on U.N. Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
here Wednesday chaired a joint meeting of the Revolutionary
Command Council and the Command of the ruling Arab Baath Socialist
Party.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported the meeting discussed the
position of the United Nations Security Council in light of the
principles announced in a statement by the decision-making body in
April 16.
</P>
<P>
The April 16 statement demanded an immediate implementation of
Paragraph 22 of the U.N. Security Council resolution 687 as a
prelude to an overall lifting of U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This paragraph provides for an easing of sanctions once all
Iraq's nuclear, chemical, biological and ballistic weapons have
been scrapped and steps taken to ensure that they cannot be
rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council's deliberations Monday have not reached
any consensus on Iraq's weapons files, so the sanctions imposed
on Iraq since 1990 will remain in place.
</P>
<P>
INA said that the Iraqi leadership decided the joint meeting
will continue to consider the report to be presented by Foreign
Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf on his contacts and talks with
the U.N. secretary-general and Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf is in New York to watch closely the discussions of
the Security Council. He is expected to come back home very soon,
INA said. 
</P>
