<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Says No to Dictates in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu held here Wednesday a third meeting with U.S. peace
envoy Dennis Ross, while reaffirming his rejection to any dictates
in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu met with Ross in the Prime Minister's Office late
in the afternoon to continue talks on the controversial U.S. peace
plan calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullback in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting Netanyahu, Ross held talks with chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat in the West Bank town Jericho
to discuss the pullback and other issues. Ross will also travel
to another West Bank city Ramallah to hold the second meeting with
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat later
in the day.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who launched the latest shuttle mission from last
Saturday, tried to persuade Netanyahu to accept the U.S. plan in
order to secure the success of the May 4 talks, to be held in
London by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright with
Netanyahu and Arafat separately.
</P>
<P>
It seemed so far that Ross has achieved little in compromising
Israel's intransigency in rejecting the U.S. plan. Netanyahu has
declared that his government would not accept any pullback
exceeding 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu repeated on Wednesday his refusal to accept what
he called "dictates" from anyone, saying Israel alone will
determine its security.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio on the eve of Israel's
50th anniversary, Netanyahu said he hoped the London talks would
achieve progress in breaking the year-long peace stalemate. But
he urged all those who wish the talks a success to make
contributions, and not Israel alone.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Israel will never accept any dictates, because
if it accepts them in the interim talks, then such tactics will be
used again in the crucial final-status talks. 
</P>
