<HEADLINE> Afghan Factions Closer to Final Accord on Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
militia and the rival Northern Alliance made significant progress
in their talks here Wednesday as the two sides agreed to nominate
20 members each for a proposed Ulema (religious scholar)
Commission.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fantastic success in my assessment," said James Ngobi,
acting head of the U.N. Special Mission for Afghanistan, after the
two sides concluded the forth day of their talks Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi told reporters that the Joint Steering Committee, made up
of five Taliban and nine alliance delegates, continued
consideration of more topics relating to the Ulema Commission,
which would decide the political setup of the future Afghan
government.
</P>
<P>
The committee decided that each side should send a delegation
of 20 members to the Ulema Commission and each delegate to the
commission will "bring a letter of guarantee and authority that
the decision taken by the commission will be implemented," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan diplomat said other matters relating to the
commission will be considered at a future session or meeting of
the steering committee.
</P>
<P>
The intra-Afghan talks ran into a deadlock earlier this week
because of differences between the two sides over the composition
of the Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said the committee has started consideration of other
items on its agenda starting with a cease-fire and the release of
POWs by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The committee decided these two items should be effected at
the time of convening the Ulema Commission," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the date for establishing the Ulema Commission
has not been set yet. "It's one of the items remaining, it is on
the agenda Thursday."
</P>
<P>
Asked if a moratorium on launching military offensives by the
two sides will hold till an agreement is reached on cease-fire, he
said this will be discussed on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
