<HEADLINE> Denktash Firm in Stances on Resuming Cyprus' Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash is standing firm in his demand for recognition of his
breakaway state as the precondition for resuming peace talks with
the government, a Greek Cypriot daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the English-language daily Cyprus Mail,
Denktash claimed that time is going "in the wrong direction"
toward "complete separation" of the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third after a failed coup by
Greek Cypriot supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Ankara against the
internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus dominated by the
Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"The Greek Cypriots should really make up their minds. Do they
want a settlement or do they want the complete division of
Cyprus?" Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that he would not go back to the negotiating
table unless his self-styled regime is recognized.
</P>
<P>
Denktash walked out of intercommunal peace talks sponsored by
the United Nations last summer in protest against European Union's
decision to start accession negotiations with the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
He insists that the negotiations be resumed on the basis of
"two states."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots do not accept the Cypriot government as
their own, Denktash said, adding the Turkish Cypriots have their
own administration, government and state.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think there is any chance of a settlement of the
Cyprus problem" if the Greek Cypriots do not accept this, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader said that he favors a four-party
conference attended by the two communities of the island, Turkey
and Greece for a solution to the protracted problem.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a visit to Cyprus on Friday by United States
Presidential Emissary Richard Holbrooke, Denktash said the
U.S. envoy will bring some ideas.
</P>
<P>
He added that he would give Holbrooke his own ideas and papers,
but refrained from elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is expected to look into ways of breaking the deadlock
in the peace process and bring the two communities back to the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and other concerned parties have been trying to help
reunify the island in a bizonal and bicommunal federation. But so
far, no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
