<HEADLINE> Cypriot Develops Method to Cure Genetic Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Cypriot scientist working in
Britain has developed a new method to treat diseases caused by
genetic problems, Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Leonidas Phylactou, who is leading an Oxford University
research team investigating ways to cure genetic diseases, told
CNA that the current study utilizes the natural abilities of a
genetic molecule called ribozyme to repair the genetic defect
that gives rise to myotonic dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
Myotonic dystrophy is a common neuromuscular genetic disease,
for which there is still no ready cure.
</P>
<P>
Phylactou said it is still early before the method can be used
in patients with myotonic dystrophy. However, its potential is
tremendous since it interferes directly with the genetic problem
and repairs by "molecular surgery."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the system can be widely applied to many other
diseases of genetic origin, he added. The findings of his current
research were published in the leading scientific journal
"Natural Genetics," on April 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
