<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The British government Wednesday
reaffirmed its opposition to the proposal of allowing two Libyans
to stand trial in a neutral country for the bombing of a Pan Am
airliner that killed 270 people over Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has imposed sanctions on Libya since
1992 for failing to extradite the two suspects named Abdel Baset
Ali Mohamed al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa Fhimah to Scotland to
face a trial.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to break the deadlock, British MP Tam Dalyell asked
the British Labor government to be more flexible in responding to
willingness by Libya to send the two suspects for trial to a
neutral place in Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett told
the House of Commons Wednesday that it would set a bad precedent
if individuals or countries accused of terrorist crimes could be
tried in the place of their choice.
</P>
<P>
"The most appropriate place is a Scottish court and the
Scottish legal system," Fatchett said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett stressed that the British and American government
positions on this issue remained unchanged and U.N. experts had
certified that the two Libyans would get a fair trial in Scotland.
