<HEADLINE> Europe to Help Modernize Egypt's Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Europe is to grant Egypt more than
1 billion dollars to help finance an industry renovation program
to be implemented over the coming three years, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This came in a statement Wednesday by Egyptian Assistant
Foreign Minister Gamal Bayoumi upon his return from Brussels,
where patcipated in a meeting of 27 European and Arab countries to
assess the European-Mediterranean partnership, better known as the
"Barcelona process."
</P>
<P>
He said the grant will be earmarked for updating Egyptian
industry before it would face strong European competition when the
policy of trade liberalization is carried out.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "this policy will not be seriously put into
effect before the year 2008," which gives Egypt enough room to
prepare for the new situation.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which ended in Brussels Tuesday, had dwelt
on the impact of a unified Europe on trade with the southern
Mediterranean states, which involve eight Arab states, namely
Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Algeria, Tunisia, Morocco and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), he said.
</P>
<P>
The partnership between the 15 EU member states and 12
countries along the southern mediterranean basin, is aimed at
developing political, economic, cultural and social ties and
establishing security. Their first conference was held in
Barcelona, Spain, in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Mediterranean foreign ministers will meet in Palermo,
Italy, in June to review all resolutions adopted during the
Barcelona meeting, Bayoumi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Four Arab countries, Morocco, Tunisia, Jordan and the PNA have
signed partnership agreements with Mediterranean EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria, Lebanon and Algeria are expected to be among the
countries which will conclude similar agreements with the EU
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
