<P>
The meeting of the Joint Steering Committee, made up of five
Taliban and nine alliance delegates, has agreed to nominate 20
members from each side to form the council of religious scholars,
James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Mission for
Afghanistan, announced here Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fantastic success in my assessment," said Ngobi, who
is presiding over the on-going talks, after the forth day of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
He said the steering committee also agreed that each delegate
to the commission, will "bring a letter of guarantee and authority
that the decision taken by the commission will be implemented."
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan diplomat said other matters relating to the
commission will be considered at a future session or meeting of
the steering committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee has also started consideration of other items on
its agenda starting with a cease-fire and the release of POWs by
the two sides and it will continue the talks on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The committee decided these two items should be effected at
the time of convening the Ulema commission," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the date for establishing the Ulema (religious
scholar) Commission has been set, Ngobi said, "Not yet, it's one
of the items remaining, it is on the agenda on Thursday."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about when the Ulema list would be
provided, he said, "It is not easy, it is not the time to say, but
it (the discussion) will continue."
</P>
<P>
The uncertainty shrouding the talks began to fade Wednesday
morning when the Taliban and the alliance suddenly softened their
positions and reached an agreement on the Ulema Commission, which
would decide the future political setup of a central government in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-point agreement, each delegation will submit a
list of Ulema for the commission; neither side will have the right
to veto any names on the proposed list; the deliberations and
decisions should be completed and implemented in accordance with
the principles of Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which has actually prevented the intra-Afghan
talks from collapsing, received warm welcome from both delegations
and the United Nations, the Organization of the Islamic
Conference, Pakistan and Iran, which have played a key role in
bringing the Afghan factions to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad and satisfied with the achievement through
dialogue," Iranian Ambassador to Pakistan Mohammad Mehdi
Akhoundzadeh told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that it would put an end to hostilities
in the war-shattered Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistan Foreign Office spokesman described the agreement as
a "landmark" that would lead to durable and lasting peace in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed his confidence that both parties would
continue their deliberations in the future in the spirit of
cooperation and accommodation, so that the Afghan people may enjoy
the peace for which they have made tremendous sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the first formal encounter between the Taliban and
the Northern Alliance, had to be suspended Monday as the two sides
bogged down in the definition of the Ulema. In the talks reopened
Tuesday afternoon, the two Afghan rivals failed to end the
impasse.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban had insisted that only those who have a degree from
institutions of Islamic education and teaching could participate
in the Ulema Commission while the alliance demanded some other
renowned figures like professors and politicians should also be
inducted into the commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
