<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-29 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Taliban Flexibility in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Wednesday called on the
Afghan Taliban militia to show flexibility in its peace talks with
rival National Islamic United Front (NIUF) in order to put an end
to the protracted civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Although the mere presence of the Taliban at the negotiations
is indicative of a turn around in their policies, this turn around
would be meaningful only if they show the flexibility needed to
reach a cease-fire, to exchange prisoners of war and to eventually
establish a broad-based government," Iran' special envoy for
Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Iran's official news agency IRNA, Boroujerdi said
that the limited authority of the Taliban delegation in Islamabad
talks, and the tough constraints they attach to their proposals,
have slowed down the progress of the talks.
</P>
<P>
There has been virtually no progress in the talks in Islamabad
between the Taliban and NIUF, led by Afghan President Burhanuddin
Rabbani whose government was driven out of capital Kabul in
September in 1996.
</P>
<P>
They could not reconcile on a list of scholars who would help
negotiate an end to the civil war.
</P>
<P>
NIUF wanted a commission of learned men of all sorts while the
Taliban, an Islamic fundamentalist group which presently rules
over two third of Afghanistan, insisted that only religious
scholars or Ulema should be included.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that Ulema are among the most respected
segment of the Afghan society, but they have had little role in
starting the war as well as its continuation.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, they can play a role regarding the crisis only if
others commit themselves to carry out their decisions," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in order to achieve peace, it is the political
leaders that should reach an understanding.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran supports the Afghan peace negotiations and regards
the Islamabad talks as a result of the first ever successful
cooperation between the U.N. and the Organization of the Islamic
Conference.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and NIUF started talks on Sunday after the
mediation by U.S. ambassador to the United Nations Bill
Richardson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
