<HEADLINE> Plane Abducted in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A small Caesna plane was
abducted by armed Somalis from the central town of Galkayo late
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitness at Galkayo airstrip, two men and a
woman have asked the pilot to take them to Nairobi after off
loading a consignment of the green stimulant leaves known as khat
in the town.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the abductors who were armed with
pistols have shortly after taking off ordered the pilot to take
them to the town of Abudwaq of the central neighboring region of
Galgudud.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the abduction is not disclosed. But reports
close to the abductors said they have been trying to escape with
money they allegedly took from their relatives and business
share-holders.
</P>
<P>
However, nearly an hour later, the plane has been seen again
landing at the rough road just two kilometers South of Galkayo
town, 600 km North of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The plane owned by a Kenyan air company, Blue Bird, has
earlier crushed after its wheels exploded and the trees beside
the road have seriously scratched its wings.
</P>
<P>
The abductors have then escaped into the jungle after seizing
all the money the pilot has with him on board the plane.
</P>
<P>
The pilot, Mohamed Dhere who is himself a Somali Kenyan, told
elders who reached him that he was safe but robbed. The pilot
said he suggested to the abductors that he could take them to
Nairobi, Adado or Beletwein town which they refused, but he said
they asked him instead to take them back to Galkayo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
