<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Reiterates Positions on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Government Spokesman Christos
Stylianides reiterated Wednesday that the Cyprus government wishes
for the resumption of negotiations under U.N. aegis with an aim
at reaching a bicommunal, bizonal federation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Stylianides said the
government remains firm in its positions on the resumption of
bicommunal talks for a settlement in Cyprus and is in expectation
of a visit here by U.S. Presidential Emissary, Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is coming to Cyprus on Friday and will remain here
until Monday, in an effort to achieve progress toward the
resumption of the stalled political dialog between President
Glafcos Clrides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The Spokesman refrained from replying to questions on the
Turkish side's position on the peace talks, which he described as
"contradicting".
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash reiterated in an interview
Wednesday that he will not participate in negotiations unless his
regime in the Turkish occupied areas of Cyprus is recognized.
</P>
<P>
But two days ago the Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman
announced that the recognition is not a precondition for
resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has demanded a change to the bicommunal basis on
which the U.N.-led peace talks are carried out, by which he and
President Clerides participated as leaders of their respective
communities.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has expressed readiness to continue
negotiations on this basis and not to accept any change that
would lead to a direct or indirect recognition of the breakaway
state in northern island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops on the island and took over the northern third in
the aftermath of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which is only
recognized by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
