<HEADLINE> 1999 Complete Sun Eclipse to Be Best Observed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A complete sun eclipse which
could be observed in Europe on August 11, 1999 and whose peak will
be in Romania is one of the most important events of this
end-millennium.
</P>
<P>
The event has aroused the entire world's attention to Romania,
both from the scientific and tourist point of view.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon is extremely rare, happening once in about 350
years. The eclipse will score its core in the nearby Ramnicu
Valcea town, South Romania, at 1104 GMT and will last two minutes
and 23 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian Astronomic Institute is the only of the kind
endowed with a solar observer on the eclipse's band.
</P>
<P>
Magda Savinschi, director of the institute, said the number of
tourists will reach half a million, meaning "an extremely large
figure for Romania's tourist capacity, given that August is a
holiday month." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Extend MONUA Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Wednesday decided to extend the mandate of the
United Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) for a further
period of two months until June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also endorsed the recommendations by the
U.N. chief to complete the withdrawal of all military personnel,
with the exception of one infantry company, the helicopter unit,
the medical support unit and 90 military observers, no later than
July 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council welcomed the recent steps taken by the
government of Angola and the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) towards completing the remaining
tasks of the Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
These include promulgation of the law granting special status
to the leader of UNITA, the appointment of the remaining governors
and vice-governors nominated by UNITA, cessation of broadcasts by
Radio Vorgan and the arrival in Luanda of senior officials of
UNITA to prepare for the establishment of UNITA headquarters in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
The council called on the government of Angola and in
particular UNITA to complete all remaining obligations under the
Lusaka Protocol and relevant Security Council resolutions,
including the normalization of state administration throughout the
national territory as well as disarmament of the civilian
population.
</P>
<P>
The council strongly condemned the attacks by members of UNITA
on the personnel of the MONUA, international personnel and Angola
national authorities, and demanded UNITA immediately stop attacks.
</P>
<P>
The council requested the U.N. secretary-general to submit a
report by June 17, 1998 on the status of the peace process, with
further recommendations regarding the mandate, size and
organizational structure of the MONUA or a follow-up United
Nations presence after June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The MONUA, established in June 1997, is aimed to supervise the
peace process in Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
