<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Labour Organization Calls for More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Labour
Organization (ILO) Wednesday called upon African leaders to
improve the lot of women workers in Sub-Saharan Africa by
providing more and better jobs for them.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered to the ongoing international conference
on 'African Women and Economic Development' which was opened at
the United Nations conference center here Tuesday, ILO deputy
director-general Mary Chinery Hesse urged African leaders to take
concrete steps to implement the resolutions adopted by the Fourth
World Conference on women held in Beijing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
She said women make up one-half of the workforce in Africa,
but their activities are concentrated only in low paid jobs,
subsistence agriculture and informal sectors.
</P>
<P>
She blamed rampant poverty and the lack of educational
opportunities for women as the primary causes of female
unemployment and underemployment.
</P>
<P>
"Until the energy and entrepreneurship of women in Africa and
elsewhere are fully recognized and nurtured as the valuable
economic asset they are, future generations of African men, women
and children risk further poverty," she warned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the four-day international conference on Wednesday
continued its deliberations on themes of globalization,
information technology, conflict, education and training, health
and population as well as leadership in 22 groups.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) in connection with its 40th
anniversary to seek ways to improve African women's social and
economic status.
</P>
<P>
The conference will reach its climax on Thursday when UN
secretary general Kofi Annan makes keynote address at the plenary
session on "Post Beijing -- the Advancement of African Women".
</P>
<P>
The conference will conclude on Friday after closing remarks
made by the UN secretary general at the forum of heads of state
and government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
