<HEADLINE> Paula Jones Files Appeal Notice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Paula Corbin Jones Wednesday
formally notified a federal judge that she was appealing the
decision that tossed out her sexual harassment lawsuit against
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The four-page notice filed Wednesday with the U.S. District
Court in Little Rock, Arkansas, said she would appeal the April 1
decision of Judge Susan Webber Wright to the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in St. Louis, Missouri, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
Her lawyers later on will file formal arguments with the
appeals court, stating the reasons they believe the judge's
decision should be overturned.
</P>
<P>
Jones announced at a news conference on April 16 in Dallas that
she would continue to fight for a chance to tell her story in
court even though it meant additional hardships for her family.
</P>
<P>
Wright said in her 40-page ruling that Jones did not have a
case "worthy of submitting to a jury." She said there was no
evidence of criminal assault or of Jones being punished on the job
after the alleged incident.
</P>
<P>
Jones claims in her lawsuit that when Clinton was governor of
Arkansas in 1991, he propositioned her in a Little Rock hotel
room. She said she rejected his advances and was later denied
promotion as a state clerk.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has repeatedly denied the allegations and said he does
not recall ever meeting Jones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
