<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Works on Detailed Plan for Post-SFOR Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- NATO ambassadors agreed
Wednesday that the follow-on force to the Stabilization Force
(SFOR) will be a transitional force with an open-ended mission
focusing on restoring public order in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors at their weekly North Atlantic Council meeting
decided to review the post-SFOR mission every six months to gauge
whether it is time to reduce the size of the follow-on force and
transfer more task to the civilian.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official, who declined to be named, said that some
benchmark criteria had been agreed at the council meeting at which
the timing for force reduction and task transfer will be judged.
</P>
<P>
The criteria included democratization, demining,
anti-corruption, return of refugees, detainment of indicted war
criminals and pluralistic way of governmental operation.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that there will also be a multinational
security unit within the follow-on force, consisting of troops
from Italy. Troops will also be contributed by Argentina and
possibly Poland.
</P>
<P>
The multinational security unit is a paramilitary force. So the
ambassadors had to discuss the coordination mechanism between this
unit and the International Police Task Force currently deployed in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-led follow-on force will also see to it that the
Bosnian local media turns non-biased while disseminating
information.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR mandate expires in mid-June and the Western military
alliance is cooperating with the United Nations Security Council
for a mandate for the follow-on force.
</P>
<P>
The official said that also on Wednesday the NATO ambassadors
met and discussed with their Russian counterpart the issue of
nuclear transparency.
</P>
<P>
The discussion, described by the official as more like a
nuclear policy seminar with photos and graphics, centered on
tactical nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Though declining to give figures, the official said that both
Russia and NATO had reduced their tactical nuclear weapons and
de-targeted the remaining tactical nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The official said that NATO had canceled three plans of
modernizing its nuclear weaponry and reduced its five types of
nuclear weapons to just one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
