<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Blood-Alcohol Limit Considered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Legislators and activists are
calling for a new nationwide drunk driving standard that would
lower the legal blood-alcohol level from the current 0.10 percent
to 0.08 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from the House of Representatives and the Senate
must decide whether to include the proposal in the final version
of a multi-billion dollar federal transportation bill.
</P>
<P>
The Senate approved the new standard by a two-thirds majority
when it crafted its version of the bill last month, but the House
Rules Committee blocked the proposal from a floor vote.
</P>
<P>
If implemented, the proposal would withhold a portion of federal
highway construction funds from states that refuse to change their
blood-alcohol standards. The government used similar tactics to
convince states to adopt lower speed limits and to increase the
legal drinking age from 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
Senator John Chaffee, a Republican and chairman of the Senate
Environment and Public Works Committee, said Wednesday he is
pressuring his colleagues on the conference committee to include
the Senate provisions in the final version of the bill. He said
the question will be resolved within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Wednesday, Chaffee and other federal and
state legislators said the drunk driving standards have triggered
incredible pressure from the beer and liquor industries.
</P>
<P>
Representative Nita Lowey, a Democrat, who sponsored an
unsuccessful attempt to bring 0.08 up for a vote in the House,
said, "The alcohol lobby spent 8 million dollars on campaign
contributions, and sadly, they now appear to have gotten their
money's worth."
</P>
<P>
Opponents say the proposal infringes on states' rights, and
would unfairly penalize social drinkers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
