<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 33 Countries Sign Kyoto Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A total of 33 countries
have signed the Kyoto Protocol on Climate Change, according to
U.N. data up to noon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We've taken a step closer to reducing greenhouse gas emissions
today," U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos Brandt told reporters at the
daily briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said 19 countries have signed it at the U.N. Headquarters
here Wednesday, including 14 European Union members, namely
Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Greece,
Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Spain, Sweden and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The 15th EU member, Ireland, is expected to sign later
Wednesday, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also signing Wednesday were Australia, Brazil, Canada, Monaco
and Norway, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kyoto Protocol, opened for signature on March
16, 1998, developed countries are bound to reduce their combined
emissions of six key greenhouse gases by at least 5 percent bellow
1990 levels by the period 2008-2012.
</P>
<P>
The protocol becomes legally binding when 55 countries, which
must include developed country parties accounting for at least 55
percent of global carbon dioxide emissions, have ratified it. So
far no country has ratified it.
</P>
<P>
Japan signed the protocol Tuesday, becoming the first signatory
from the major developed countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
