<HEADLINE> Shortage of Foreign Exchange in Zambia to End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The current shortage of foreign
exchange in Zambia is expected to end soon following a major plan
worked out with the assistance of the World Bank to boost its
copper production and export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Zambia governor Jacob Mwanza said here Wednesday that
the survival plan, coupled with increased export of
non-traditional goods, are expected to earn the country enough
foreign exchange to offset the current shortage on the financial
market.
</P>
<P>
The governor of the country's central bank told a weekly news
briefing at the State House that the shortage of foreign currency
has been caused by a number of factors such as the decline of
copper production and prices of the commodity at the London
market, non-release of donor aid to the country and the
importation of 250 tons of maize and mealie meal worth over 40
million U.S. Dollars between October 1997 and March this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the harvest season will see a reduction in food
imports thereby saving the scarce foreign currency while the
increase in the exports of cash crops such as soya beans,
sunflower and cotton will also help to stabilize the financial
market.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza said the central bank will through the open market
operations syphon excess local currency in circulation in order
to bring down inflation which rocketed by more than 20 percent
last month.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that the next Paris Club meeting to be
held next month will give his couuntry a better change for
bilateral aid flow as well as help it qualify for debt relief
through the highly indeted poor countries initiative of the World
Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza also said that debt servicing has contributed to the
shortage of foreign currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
