<HEADLINE> UK Says No Breakthrough Expected at London Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- British government officials said
here Wednesday the Middle East peace talks to be held in London
next Monday are unlikely to achieve major breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will chair the
one-day talks, at which Israel and the Palestinians are expected
to discuss new American peace proposals, calling on Israel to
withdraw from 13 percent of West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Wednesday afternoon,
"You can see from the noises coming from various quarters that
people are not expecting any significant breakthrough."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
said Tuesday that it was up to the Palestinians to break the
deadlock and insisted that Israel should not risk its security for
a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that British Prime Minister Tony Blair is
expected to hold separate talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat in London, but
made it clear that Britain would play a complementary role.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook played down the
prospect of substantial progress at the London talks by saying
Wednesday, "While there has been a commitment from both sides to
come, there has been no commitment to any specific deal."
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to have the opportunity to help advance the
(Middle East peace) process, but it will be difficult," Cook said.
</P>
