<HEADLINE> Africa Has a Special Place Within INTELSAT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Africa has a very special place
within the International Telecommunications Satellite
Organization (INTELSAT) now and in the future, INTELSATt director
general said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening meeting of the INTELSAT Africa group one,
Irving Goldstein said that out of 142 members 42 are African
countries and many African countries depend on INTELSAT
satellites for their communications lifeline to the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 INTELSAT's revenue from Africa totaled over 84 million
U.S. Dollars, an increase of 15 percent over 1996 and 60 percent
since 1994, he said.
</P>
<P>
Along with technological advancement, privatization,
liberalization, increasing investment and competition are the
driving forces behind the growth of telecommunications, he said.
</P>
<P>
Whatever changes INTELSAT, which was founded in 1964, is
experiencing as a result of the increased competition, its
commitment to the development of telecommunications on African
continent will remain as strong as ever, he promised.
</P>
<P>
In fact, about 60 percent of INTELSAT's assistance and
development activities are concentrated on African customers and
this forms an integral part of INTELSAT's sales and marketing
effort, said Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
Eleven countries including Namibia, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia,
Mauritius, Ghana and Angola are represented at the on-going
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
