<HEADLINE> Turkey Insists on Bilateral Talks for Resolving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Wednesday reiterated that
its disputes over some Aegean islets with Greece should be
resolved through bilateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The problems between the two countries are so serious that
they can not be discussed in multilateral meetings," Turkish
Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan told a weekly press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Utkan rejected as "unacceptable to Turkey" the recent remarks
by Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos which claimed
sovereignty over the disputed islets.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over a number of issues
relating to the Aegean Sea, including the air space, sea-bed
minerals as well as sovereignty over some small uninhabited
islands.
</P>
<P>
In February, Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem proposed
bilateral discussions on the Aegean issues but was rejected by
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Athens insists that the disputes be settled through arbitration
by the Hague-based U.N. International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
"Such a stance of Greece has made a solution to the thorny issue
more difficult," the Turkish spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
