to negotiate or mediate," the official said. "That's for others."
</P>
<P>
Gore will meet with Israel Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Gore's trip to the Middle East was seen here as new U.S.
efforts to send a message to Middle East leaders, especially the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders, that the Clinton administration
would not let the year-long stalemate of the peace process
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"The vice president will be reinforcing our basic message --
that we'll be there for them if they take risks for peace," one
senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will start separate talks
with Netanyahu and Arafat in London on May 4, the day Gore winds
up his Middle East trip.
</P>
<P>
Washington has cautioned the public not to pin great hope on
the upcoming London meetings as a U.S. proposal on percentage of
Israel's withdrawal from the West Bank was again rejected last
week by Netanyahu after his talks with U.S. special envoy Dennis
Ross. 
