<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Fully Implement UN Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nairobi, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela who is visiting Angola Wednesday said that his government
will fully implement United Nations sanctions against the rebel
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
According to information reaching here, the South African
President, speaking at the Angolan National Assembly, said that
South Africa "is ready to play whatever part it can in helping to
ensure that the provisions of the Lusaka Protocol are met and
that (U.N.) Security Council resolutions are adhered to."
</P>
<P>
President Mandels who is on his first state visit to Angola
told Angolan President Jose Dos Santos and the parliament that
his government as a member of the United Nations and the Southern
African Development Community is doing everything to comply with
the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Among other things, we have tightened control and
surveillance at airports that were being used to destabilize the
peace for which Angola has been working," said the South African
president.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa unequivocally supports the peace process,"
President Mandela said, adding that his government looks forward
eagerly to the final implementation of the provisions in a
peaceful manner.
</P>
<P>
He said that the full realization of the potential for the two
nations to draw mutual benefit from their relationship with each
other, hinges on the success of the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are encouraged by the recent steps that have been taken in
compliance with the Lusaka Protocol," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He congratulated all those involved for putting the interests
of the whole nation before all else.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela also thanked Angola for the democracy it
helped his country achieve, saying that democracy "has brought us
opportunity to address the basic needs of our people."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the large business delegation accompanying him
testified to the fact that South African companies wish to lose
no opportunity to expand trade and investment ties between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that President Mandela will not meet UNITA
leader Jonas Savimbi who has fear for his own safety and won't
leave his headquarters in central Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
