<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4,800 Cases of Breast Cancer Recorded in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- There are a total of 4,800 new
cases of breast cancer in Greece each year.
</P>
<P>
In Greece, 1,100 to 1,200 new cases of ovarian cancer are also
recorded annually, according to Greece's Athens News newspaper
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Greek experts believe that both breast and ovarian cancer are
hereditary and can be detected at an early stage through a blood
test which identifies genes known as BRC1 and BRC2.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 50,000 women in Greece are believed to carry the
gene and one in 10 women with breast cancer in Greece would have
inherited the trait.
</P>
<P>
BRC1 has been reportedly found in 87 percent of women with
cancer in one breast, in 50 percent of women with cancer in both
breasts and in 40-60 percent of women with ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
Experimental tests being conducted at two private Athens
hospitals and the state-run Agios Savvas hospital are now
providing Greek specialists with the hope of gauging a woman's
genetic predisposition to developing the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
