<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Group to Further Enhance Members' Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank (ADB)
Group Wednesday pledged to further enhance the development of its
regional members so as to play a more active role in the
continent's development.
</P>
<P>
This is the aim of the group's current development policy and
operational objectives, said Beita Yusuf, an executive director
of ADB at the Pre-1998 ADB Annual Meetings Forum held here.
</P>
<P>
The ADB Group was established in 1964 for the purpose of
promoting the economic development and social development of the
African members of ADB.
</P>
<P>
The group consists of ADB, the African Development Fund (ADF)
and the Nigeria Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
According to Yusuf, the current development policy priorities
of the group emanate from Africa's overarching development
objectives, which focus on accelerating production growth,
promoting human resource development, reducing poverty and
establishing foundations for long-term sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
A substantial share of the group's resources will be accorded
to projects and programs in the agricultural and social sectors
because of their direct effects on poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The group, as a matter of fact, has mobilized and deployed
resources over the past years to finance projects and programs of
its regional member countries.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the bank group had cumulatively approved
over 2,000 loans and grants amounting to more than 33 billion
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The commitments, according to Yusuf, were made to 52 countries
and multinational institutions to support projects and programs
in agriculture, transport, public utilities, industry, education
and health.
</P>
<P>
It has also co-financed policy-based loans to support
adjustment and reform programs of governments of member countries
with an aim to enhance efficiency and the macro-economic
environment, Yusuf said.
</P>
<P>
The group's role in the development of Africa is also
reflected by its active involvement in the international
initiative for the Highly Indebted Poor Countries, which is aimed
at reducing the debts of eligible countries to sustainable
levels.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the group will enhance its catalytic role in private
sector financing, the official added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
