<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Finance "Enclave" Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank (ADB)
is to give more investment to export-oriented, commercial
projects in a fresh bid to boost the development of regional
member countries.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors of ADB has just approved proposals to
introduce the financing of "enclave" projects in these countries,
Beita Yusuf, an executive director of ADB, disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The detailed guidelines should be finalized in the second half
of this year, he said in his keynote address at the Pre-1998 ADB
Annual Meetings Forum held here.
</P>
<P>
Enclave projects, Yusuf explained, are those "whose operations
are export-oriented and are run on commercial basis and can,
therefore, take and repay loans without assistance from the
government."
</P>
<P>
Such projects could be publicly or privately owned or a
combination of both ownership, with the main difference lying in
the size of ADB investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
While for normal private sector operations, the bank's
investment is generally limited to about 15 million U.S. Dollars
per project, enclave projects could be as high as 50 million U.S.
Dollars each.
</P>
<P>
According to Yusuf, this is an area where some of the
parastatals being privatized could benefit. But he did not
further elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
