<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Health Insurers Sue Tobacco Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A United States coalition
representing health insurers from at least 35 states Wednesday
filed lawsuits against major tobacco companies, seeking
compensation for treating smoking-related illness.
</P>
<P>
The Coalition for Tobacco Responsibility, a network
representing 25 million Blue Cross and Blue Shield insurance
policyholders, said they had filed the suits in federal courts in
New York, Chicago and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
"These suits are our effort to begin to improve public health
by changing the behavior of the tobacco industry," said Michael
McGarvey, chief medical officer of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
New Jersey, told a Washington news conference.
</P>
<P>
McGarvey said, "We are accusing the tobacco industry of
conspiracy, fraud, misrepresentation and violation of federal
racketeering and anti-trust laws."
</P>
<P>
The lawsuits allege that the tobacco industry concealed the
addictive nature of smoking, manipulated nicotine levels to make
cigarettes more addictive and conducted research and marketing
campaigns targeting teen-agers and children.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury Department said that direct health care costs by
tobacco-related illnesses reach 60 billion U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Blue Cross and Blue Shield provides health care coverage for
one in four Americans, or 68.7 million people, in all 50 states.
The amount of compensation the coalition is seeking for could be
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new lawsuits dramatically escalate the troubles of the
tobacco companies, which are under attack from the federal
government, states and public health advocates.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco companies had hoped to end most of the litigation
against them in a proposed settlement they negotiated with states
last June. But this month they abandoned efforts to get that
agreement approved by Congress and instead vowed to defend
themselves in court.
</P>
<P>
But President Bill Clinton has taken a hard line against Big
Tobacco, urging the industry to stop marketing to young people and
warning that legislation will come with or without industry
participation.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the nation's fifth biggest cigarette company,
Liggett Group, agreed to cooperate in the government's criminal
investigation of the tobacco industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
