<HEADLINE> G8 Urged to Guard Against Euro as Source of Volatility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Eight (G8) leading
industrialized nations was urged Wednesday to make joint efforts
to ensure that the coming single European currency named euro
would not become a source of global financial volatility.
</P>
<P>
The International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) said in a statement
issued ahead of next month's G8 summit in Birmingham, England,
that leading industrial governments and businesses should work
more closely together to design the rules for the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which was delivered to G8 summit host British
Prime Minister Tony Blair by ICC President Helmut Maucher, said:
"As markets become increasingly global, so the need is rapidly
growing for more global rule-setting. And that means global
decision-making and leadership."
</P>
<P>
Maucher made it clear in the statement that the planned launch
of the single currency in January 1999 was a welcome aspect of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
"But the introduction of the euro will require governments and
central bankers across the world, but particularly in G8
countries, to collaborate to ensure that this major development is
handled efficiently and does not become a source of global
financial volatility," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Asia's financial crisis had also demonstrated
the need for a stronger framework of laws, rules and institutions
to ensure the smooth running of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
"It would be unfortunate if the Asian crisis contributed to a
growing perception in the public mind that the process known as
globalization is a threat rather than an opportunity," he said in
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The G8 comprises the United States, Japan, France, Italy,
Germany, Canada, Britain and Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
