<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Urges ADB for Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) Wednesday called on the African
Development Bank (ADB) to amend its charter in a view to better
supporting the economic integration efforts of the regional
economic groupings.
</P>
<P>
The important thing at present is how to develop a working
relationship and modalities between ADB and Africa's major five
regional economic groupings that do not violate the charter of
the respective institutions, a senior ECOWAS official said.
</P>
<P>
There are great possibilities for cooperation between ADB and
such groupings, R.D. Asante, head of ECOWAS money and payments
division, said in a keynote address at the Pre-1998 ADB Annual
Meetings Forum held here.
</P>
<P>
According to Asante, who spoke on behalf of the ECOWAS
Executive Secretariat, ADB's involvement in regional integration
programs has been low because it was set up at a time when
regional cooperation and integration schemes were not on the
cards.
</P>
<P>
"To enable the ADB to pay a more positive role in promoting
regional economic integration activities through the provision of
financial resources and technical assistance, its charter would
have to be amended to include provisions that make room for
financing regional integration activities of African countries,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he went on, ADB should assist regional economic
groupings by mobilizing the support of other international
financial institutions for regional economic integration, apart
from its own efforts to manage the matter.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that ADB create a department of African economic
integration to formulate policies and strategies, and to provide
advice, monitor and follow-up on implementation of cooperation
programs.
</P>
<P>
ADB should also create a special fund for African economic
integration, he added.
</P>
<P>
ADB is to hold its 1998 annual meeting in late May in Abidjan,
Cote d'Ivoire, where its headquarters is based.  
</P>
</TEXT>
