<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Settle Dispute with Arabs Through Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Majlis (parliament)
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri Wednesday his country is willing to
settle disputes with Arab neighbors through "constructive dialog."
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference before winding up a three-day visit
here that "the lull or the so-called chill (between Iran and Gulf
Arab countries) is on its way to vanish."
</P>
<P>
He said Tehran is awaiting visits by officials of the United
Arab Emirates to solve their territorial dispute over the three
islands of Abu Mussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs near the Strait
of Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of referring the dispute to the
U.N. International Court of Justice in the Hague, saying "by doing
so, we are allowing the issue to be given a political angle."
</P>
<P>
Nouri, who arrived here Monday on his second official visit
since 1995, expressed satisfaction over bilateral relations and
the result of his visit.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Nouri met with Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah and his Kuwaiti counterpart Ahmed Abdul Aziz Al-Sadoun on
Iran's ties with Gulf Arab states as well as improvement of
bilateral ties and issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Nouri denied media reports that there existed illegal trade of
oil between Iraq and Iran, which is a violation of the
U.N. sanctions against Iraq imposed since 1990.
</P>
<P>
He assured that Iran's relations with Iraq would not affect the
its stand that Baghdad must implement all the Security Council
resolutions related to its 1990-91 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Nouri stressed the importance of exchange of visits between
senior Iranian officials and their Arab counterparts, which he
said is "an opportunity to open dialog that would help remove the
existing" mistrust.
</P>
<P>
Last year Iran made goodwill gestures to improve ties with the
Gulf Arab states which had been strained since Iran's Islamic
Revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have since taken steps to upgrade the level of
relations, believing that building strong ties is vital for
security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
In May 1997, Kuwait and Iran signed a bilateral memorandum of
understanding on all aspects of economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Nouri has suggested the establishment of a joint center for
regional studies as a step towards developing scientific
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
