<HEADLINE> Palestinian Says U.S. Credibility Affected in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. bias toward Israel "has
severely affected American credibility and standing" in the Middle
East, a top Palestinian official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of attitude has led to the very open charge of
double standards and lack of evenhandedness in the way in which
the U.S. has dealt with the peace process and therefore it has
affected its standing and interests and credibility in the
region," Hanan Ashrawi, the Palestinian higher education
minister, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
Her comment came just days before Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright is to hold separate meetings in London with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi said Palestinian leaders will be in London to see
whether the United States will be willing to take a firm stand
against what she described as Israel's unwillingness to abide by
commitments to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to give them the benefit of the doubt for one
more meeting," she said.
</P>
<P>
As for U.S. suggestions that it might wind up its mediation
in the peace process because of the unwillingness of Israel and
the Palestinians to negotiate seriously, Ashrawi said: "I don't
take the threats that seriously."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. can't afford to withdraw" with its huge interests
in the region, she said.
</P>
<P>
But she envisioned the possibility of an increased European
role in Middle East diplomacy.  
</P>
