<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Chief Economist Recommended to Be ECB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The German cabinet Wednesday decided
to nominate Itmar Issing, the chief economist of the German
central bank Bundesbank, to be the German representative in the
planned six-member executive board of the future Europe central
bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
The nomination of Issing, who is seen as a staunch defender of
the Bundesbank's tight-money policy, will help to guarantee the
independence of the ECB, said German Finance Minister Theo Waigel.
</P>
<P>
The final decision on the composition of the six-member ECB
executive board is expected to be made at the European Union
leaders' summit meeting on May 1-2 in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
However, the most contraversial issue at the summit will prove
to be the selection of the first president of the new bank.
</P>
<P>
Germany and most other EU states expect the former Dutch
central bank chief Wim Duisenberg to take the EU's top monetary
job. France, however, has insisted that its own central bank
governor, Jean-Claude Trichet deserves the post.
</P>
<P>
With the EU summit only two days away, there is still no sign
of an agreement yet.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the dispute over the ECB leadership is
largely a confrontation between Germany and France about who will
hold control over future European monetary policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
