<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges INTELSAT to Continue Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Wednesday urged the
International Telecommunications Satellite Organization
(INTELSAT) to continue developing advanced and cheap digital
systems solutions for developing countries like Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Opening the INTELSAT Africa Group One meeting here Wednesday,
Zambian Minister of Communications and Transport Anoshi Chipawa
said that the digital systems will enable a number of developing
countries to have direct connections among themselves and thus
reduce the transit charges which are usually very high.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister also called on INTELSAT to continue
developing affordable products with reputable companies that can
easily be installed in remote rural areas in order to provide the
basic telephone service.
</P>
<P>
"This would be responding to the needs of the majority of our
people who live in the rural areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the two-day meeting that "meaningful development
cannot be achieved in any country if its telecommunication
infrastructure remains undeveloped."
</P>
<P>
Satellite communications now form an integral part of our new
"wired" world, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Although submarine cable is now more frequently used to
connect the continents of the world with readily available
telephone circuits, he said, only satellite communications have
enabled completely reliable communication links of telephone,
television and data transmission to be provided over all types of
terrestrial obstacles.
</P>
<P>
As early as 1970, Zambia had realized the potential of
satellite communications in providing international links for
telephone, television and data communications.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, Mwembeshi-IA Earth Station was commissioned in
ushering the dawn of satellite communications in the country and
the station enables Zambia to be connected to a number of
European and Asian countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has benefitted from the INTELSAT digitalization loan
program through which INTELSAT gave Zambia a loan of 2.2 million
U.S. Dollars for the Zambia Telecommunications Company to
digitalize its Mwembeshi-IA Earth Station, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Africa is divided into two zones. Africa Group One mainly
comprises the English-speaking countries and Africa Group Two is
mainly Francophone.
</P>
<P>
Eleven countries including Namibia, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia,
Mauritius, Ghana and Angola are represented at the on-going
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
