<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Says No EU Expansion if Problems Created </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Greece warned Thursday that there
would be no European Union (EU) expansion if anyone created a
political problem over Cyprus' accession course.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the Athens afternoon daily
Eleftherotypia, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said
that Cyprus was part of a package with the other membership
candidates.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations would be held separately with each candidate and
each candidate would be judged on the basis of its pros and cons,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister warned that if someone created a political issue
over Cyprus, this would create a political issue of the
community's function in its entirety. Therefore, he said, there
would be no smoothly functioning community and, consequently,
there would be no enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive-coup
backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Cyprus was included by the EU in its list of
countries waiting to join the community. The divided island
republic began at the end of March its accession negotiations with
the EU. All this led to the opposition of northern Cyprus and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
To protest against the EU's above-mentioned decision, northern
Cyprus suspended its negotiations with the Cyprus government for
the final settlement of the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Just before the May 1 visit to Cyprus by U.S. presidential
envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash repeated Wednesday that peace talks between the island's
two communities could be resumed only if his northern Cyprus was
recognized.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, the Greek government is now under
extreme pressure from its European partners and the United States
to first lift its veto on EU financial packages destined for
Turkey and then to recognize northern Cyprus, which declared its
independence from the Republic of Cyprus in 1983 and has been
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts believe that Athens is sending a clear
message to its EU partners and other countries such as the United
States that Greece firmly supports Cyprus' efforts to join the EU
and no one should try to make troubles in Cyprus' accession
course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
