<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bougainville Cease-fire Signed After Last-Minute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Warring factions on Papua New
Guinea(PNG)'s Bougainville island Thursday declared an end to the
island's bloody 10-year secessionist conflict as they signed a
cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The war is over -- now it's up to us to protect the peace,"
rebel military commander Sam Kauona told hundreds gathering in
Arawa, Bougainville, for a formal peace ceremony and a symbolic
laying-down of arms, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Islanders broke arrows and handed over spears amid singing and
dancing at the ceremony, attended by PNG Prime Minister Bill Skate
and witnessed by Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and
New Zealand Foreign Minister Don McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
The permanent cease-fire, signed by anti- and pro-government
factions and the PNG government itself, comes into effect at
midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire came after nine months of New Zealand-brokered
talks aimed at ending the conflict, which began in 1988 with
landowner disputes over the world-famous Panguna copper mine, and
escalated into a war for independence from PNG after the mine
closed in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's cease-fire was only finalized after an 11th-hour
hiccup threatened to derail the agreement, the Australian wire
service said in a dispatch from Arawa.
</P>
<P>
Secessionist rebel leaders and PNG officials were locked in an
impasse Wednesday night over technicalities in implementing the
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
However, a compromise was reached at 3 a.m. local time after
overnight talks aboard the Australian naval vessel HMAS Tobruk,
which was moored off the war-ravaged island's central coast.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stops the carrying, manufacture and distribution
of weapons and assures freedom of movement on the island, where an
estimated 15,000 lives have been lost in the conflict, the wire
service said.
</P>
<P>
The PNG government has also agreed to a phased withdrawal of
troops from Bougainville, which will be dependent on a civil
police force being established, while Arawa will be declared a
demilitarized zone.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's ceremony was marred by the absence of the rebels'
reclusive political leader, Bougainville Interim Government
President Francis Ona, who has become isolated from the rest of
the rebel leadership and refused to back the current peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Ona's deputy Joseph Kabui attended Thursday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Australian troops will make up the majority of a multi-nation
300-member Peace Monitoring Group on the island which will assume
duties after the cease-fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
