<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The European Union (EU) has agreed to provide Egypt 1
billion U.S. dollars in grants in the coming 20 years for its
industry renovation programs.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister Gamal Bayoumi said
Wednesday that this was the first time for the EU to give such
economic assistance to a non-European state.
</P>
<P>
Four Arab states, Morocco, Tunisia, Jordan and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) have signed partnership agreements with
the EU. And Egypt, Syria, Lebanon and Algeria are expected to be
among the countries which will conclude similar agreements with
the EU soon.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- North Sinai Governor Ali Hefzi said Wednesday a
national project for developing North Sinai governorate to the
year 2017 needs 75 billion pounds (about 22.06 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hefzi said that 3.53 billion dollars have been used for
infrastructure projects in the governorate over the past 10 years
aimed at settling 3 million people and creating 800,000 jobs for
young people.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The executive council of the International Fund for
Agricultural Development has decided to give the PNA 26 million
dollars in loans.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Agriculture Minister Abdul Jawad Saleh said that
the money, with a maturity of 40 years and an interest rate of
less than 1 percent, would be effectively used for developing its
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- Bahrain and Britain signed an air transport agreement
in London Wednesday, Lebanese newspaper "Al-Hayat" said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini Minister of Communications Sheikh Ali Bin Khalifa Bin
Salman al-Khalifa said that the 19-point agreement addresses air
transport rights of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Gulf Air and the British Airways are flying 21
flights a week between Manama and London.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- French food exports to Saudi Arabia in 1997 reached
1.25 billion Saudi riyals (about 330 million dollars), up 10
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The French Commercial Attache said that France was the second
biggest foodstuff exporter to Saudi Arabia, with its foodstuffs
accounting for 7.2 percent of the total local need. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
