<HEADLINE> China to Meet 1998 Targets: Chinese Bank Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China's economic performance in
1998 will be better than that of 1997, said a Chinese bank
official here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China will meet major economic targets for 1998 such as a GDP
growth of eight percent and a rise of less than three percent in
the consumer price index, said Yin Jieyan, the alternate governor
of the People's Bank of China. He made the comment at a session of
the 31st annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Having met the general objectives of sustained growth while
maintaining stability, China's economy delivered its best
performance in 1997 since the country adopted the policy of reform
and opening up in 1978," said Yin, head of the Chinese delegation
attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"1998 will be a crucial year for China to push ahead with
economic reform, opening up and its modernization drive," he added.
</P>
<P>
He told the session that the newly-elected Chinese government
will strengthen the fundamental economic status of the
agricultural sector, expand investment in infrastructure, speed up
the transformation of various state-owned enterprises, intensify
economic structure readjustment, and further integrate the Chinese
economy with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts will be made to improve the quality of growth so as to
sustain rapid and healthy economic development as well as social
progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The appropriately stringent fiscal and monetary policies will
continue and financial regulation will be improved," he said.
"Inflation will be contained and financial risks prevented and
mitigated."
</P>
<P>
Yin said that a social security network will be established to
ensure stable the macroeconomic environment.
</P>
<P>
He believes that China's economic performance in 1998 will
improve over 1997 as a result of the proposed efforts by the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
