<HEADLINE> U.S. Should Stop Bullying Cuba, Chretien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States should stop
trying to bully Cuban President Fidel Castro into change, Canadian
Prime Minister Jean Chretien said after his return from an
official visit to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The decades-old U.S. economic embargo and other pressure
tactics are hurting the Cuban people needlessly, Chretien was
quoted as saying in published reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chretien was particularly concerned that the embargo deprived
Cubans of anesthetics and other medicines.
</P>
<P>
"I am told that dentists do not have the proper anesthesia to
serve the people," he said in an interview with CNN after his
return.
</P>
<P>
This is not the way a rich and powerful country like the United
States should behave toward a smaller neighbor, Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
"When you are that powerful, that is the time to be benevolent,
to be nice, not to show your muscle," Chretien noted.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian prime minister, who will host the next Summit of
Americas in three years, said he is not sure yet whether he will
invite Mr. Castro to attend the future event.
</P>
<P>
At the most recent summit meeting earlier this month, Latin
American and Caribbean leaders were reported to have reached a
broad consensus on bringing Cuba into the hemispheric integration
process. 
</P>
