<HEADLINE> Chinese Bank Official Calls for Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese bank official called for
regional and global cooperation Thursday in preventing excessive
financial assaults by international speculative capital and in
maintaining world financial order.
</P>
<P>
"We encourage regional financial cooperation in Asia and are
willing to participate in discussions on possible cooperation
mechanisms," Yin Jieyan, the alternate governor of the People's
Bank of China said at a session of the 31st annual meeting of the
the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
"With the increasing globalization of the world economy, many
causes can lead to a systemic financial crisis," said Yin, who led
the Chinese delegation to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He believes that a secure and stable financial system
constitutes the cornerstone for the stability and development of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Yin said he is pleased to see that some of the countries
affected by the Asian financial crisis have already started to
recover, which shows that Asia will continue to be one of the most
dynamic economic regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
Asked why China has fended off a potential financial crisis and
sustained sound economic development, the Chinese central bank
leader outlined the following major reasons: rapid and healthy
economic development, prudent financial policies, a strong balance
of payments position, sufficient foreign exchange reserves, and a
rational external debt structure.
</P>
<P>
"As a developing country, China has an urgent need to develop
its economy," Yin pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He told the session however that to maintain regional economic
stability and help crisis-hit countries get out of difficulties
quickly, China has contributed through international financial
organizations such as the International Monetary Fund and with
bilateral arrangements to the countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said China has on many occasions reiterated its
commitment to a stable Renminbi exchange rate, for which China
will pay a certain price.
</P>
<P>
"We think it worthwhile as long as the announcement not to
devalue Renminbi continues to remain beneficial and conducive to
the maintenance of financial stability in Asia and the world at
large and it is the best way to support economic recovery in East
and Southeast Asia," Yin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
