<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Discusses Israeli Offer with Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 30 (Xinhua) -- European Union's Middle East envoy
Miguel Moratinos held talks on Thursday with Lebanese leaders on
Israel's offer of a conditional pullback from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day visit here following a trip to Syria,
Moratinos met with Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berry, Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri and Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
The envoy told reporters after talks with Boueiz that during
discussions with Lebanese and Syrian leaders, he reaffirmed EU's
support for Lebanon's position on the Israeli offer.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to endorse the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 425 which demands a unilateral Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon, but requested Lebanese government to
guarantee Israel's northern security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree to coordinate their stances on
key issues, have rejected the offer. They insist that the Israeli
withdrawal be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon to allegedly protect its northern areas from
cross-border attacks by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said that under the request of Israel, he has
conveyed some ideas of the Jewish state on the pullback proposal
to Lebanese leaders. But he refused to go into the details.
</P>
<P>
He had reportedly held talks on the Israeli proposal with a
senior Israeli official in Cyprus before embarking on the trip to
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said that he also discussed with leaders of Syria and
Lebanon various ways of reviving the peace talks between Syria and
Lebanon on one side and Israel on the other.
</P>
<P>
The talks came to a standstill in early 1996 after a series of
suicide bombings in Israel. Syria wants the return of its Golan
Heights, which Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos has left here for Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
