<HEADLINE> River Blindness Coming Down in W. Africa: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Africa regional Director of
the World Health Organization (WHO) has said the onchocerciasis
control program (OCP), which was set up to bring down river
blindness in 11 west African states, has achieved its objective.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Malick Samba told the Zimbabwe News Agency in Harare
Thursday the program was scheduled to end by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
He said more than 10 percent of the population of the 11
countries used to be blind before it was introduced.
</P>
<P>
''Now nobody in the area risks being blind because of river
blindness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
By the time it winds up it would have protected 40 million
people from river blindness.
</P>
<P>
The countries covered by the program are Benin, Burkina Faso,
Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Guinea, Guinea Bissau, Mali, Niger,
Senegal, Sierra Leone and Togo.
</P>
<P>
OCP, which is based in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, is sponsored
by the World Bank, United Nations Development Program, the U.N.
Food and Agriculture Organization and WHO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
