<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Exports Remain Major Contributors to Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Li Shengjiang
</P>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Can China's export trade grow
at a rate higher than that of the national economy in 1998, as it
did for the past two decades?
</P>
<P>
Can exports contribute two percentage points to the projected
eight percent growth in GDP this year, as the central government
hopes?
</P>
<P>
Certain factors are leading to a positive answer to the above
questions.
</P>
<P>
China set this year's export target at 200 billion US dollars,
which is an impressive growth for one year of 10 percent, taking into
account the impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
To the delight of trade policy makers, exports climbed 13.2
percent in the first quarter, six percentage points higher than
the GDP growth in the same period.
</P>
<P>
"So long as we are working in the right direction, we'll be
able to overcome the impact of the financial crisis," said Liu
Xiangdong, assistant minister of foreign trade and Economic
Cooperation. Liu was in Guangzhou to attend the 83th China Export
Commodities Fair, which closed today.
</P>
<P>
The success of the fair also further enhances the belief that
China is able to meet its export goal this year.
</P>
<P>
The pinch of the financial crisis could be widely felt during
the fair, as the number of buyers as well as orders from Southeast
Asian countries shrank.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese trade experts have noted that Southeast Asia,
after all, accounts for only about seven percent of China's total
exports. Moreover, demand from the region for daily-use items and
raw materials remains robust during the fair.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the optimism is the fact that orders from
long-distance and newly-emerging markets in Western and Eastern
Europe, the United States, the Commonwealth of Independent States,
East Europe, Africa and Latin America rose drastically,
contributing greatly to a near-record 10.2 billion US
dollars-worth of deals clinched during the fair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Exports Remain Major Contributors to Economic Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Because of brisk business with neighboring countries, many
Chinese exporters in the past were reluctant to engage in
ocean-going trade. Now they are taking the initiative to do so,"
Zhou noted.
</P>
<P>
The fair was also a convincing illustration of to what extent
the opening-up of new markets can help China offset the impact of
the financial crisis on its exports.
</P>
<P>
For example, Guangdong Province, which is a heavyweight
exporter, accounting for one fourth of the country's exports,
received over 10 percent more orders during the fair, with over 70
percent from newly-emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
Though coastal Shandong Province calls itself a "major victim"
due to its close business ties with the Republic of Korea (ROK),
it still managed to score a 16 percent increase in orders, also
due to diversified trade.
</P>
<P>
China's leading four exporters -- Guangdong, Jiangsu, Shanghai,
and Shandong -- all performed well during the fair, convincing trade
authorities that the four regions can achieve projected export
growth of between 10 and 15 percent. "If the goal is met, it will
mean a 60 percent guarantee for hitting the national export
target," trade officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Jianhua, a Shanghai trade official, that east
China metropolis has stepped up its efforts to offset the crisis
by further tapping new markets and developing high-tech and
high-value-added products, especially information-related products.
</P>
<P>
There are also other favorable factors for China's exports,
trade experts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
A comparatively stronger Renminbi can benefit China's purchase
of raw and semi-finished materials from Southeast Asia and help
boost the processing trade, which make up half of the country's
exports.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the steady growth in exports by Sino-foreign joint
ventures and solely-owned foreign enterprises, and the granting
independent foreign trade rights to more Chinese enterprises will
also guarantee the sustained growth of exports, they noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
