<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emigration Tide Ebbs in Kyrgyzstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Housing, unemployment and the
education of children -- some of the problems besetting the
pioneering Kyrgyzian emigrants abroad -- have led more would-be
emigrants to stay home.
</P>
<P>
1997 saw 11,000 emigrants leave Kyrgyzstan compared to 1993,
when over 140,000 people left the country. About 6,000 to 8,000
emigrants are returning to Kyrgyzstan annually, according to the
latest issue of the "Asian Economy and Life" weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
The emigration tide in the Kyrgyz Republic can be traced back
to the country's independence in 1991. Since then, many
non-Kyrgyzian people, mainly ethnic Russians, have been trying to
return to their native lands.
</P>
<P>
Their motherlands however are not quick to welcome them as they
vanguards eventually find out after obtaining permanent
residence. The migrants have to face more difficulties in seeking
housing and jobs, and their children have less access to education.
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit to Kyrgyzstan by Tatiana Regent, director
of the Immigration Board of the Russian Federation, Kyrgyzstan and
Russia signed an agreement to provide legal protection to
Russian-speaking people in their attempt to immigrate to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the Russian official pointed out, would lay the
legal groundwork for the protection of the migrants' civil
rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Degree Awarding Program to Promote Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Institute of
Education (HKIEd) announced here Thursday that it will offer a
four-year full-time degree program in primary education for
secondary school graduates beginning this fall, the first of its
kind in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Named the Bachelor of Education Program, it includes three
special features: a strong focus on languages, a special emphasis
on civic education and the use of information technology in
pedagogy and classroom practice, said professor Ruth Hayhoe,
director of the HKIEd, at a press conference held on Thursday to
launch the professional four-year degree programs.
</P>
<P>
Hayhoe said that the program creates a new choice for secondary
school graduates who wish to become primary school teachers as it
provides a sound basis for its graduates to work competently as
beginning primary school teachers and to develop continuously in
meeting the challenges facing primary school education in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
"The program had been designed to produce knowledgeable and
professional teachers thus helping to contribute to Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa's
stated objectives of attaining 35 percent graduate posts for all
primary schools at the advanced date of year 2001 instead of
2007," Hayhoe said.
</P>
<P>
The program's strong language focus is motivated by a concern
about the adequacy of standards of language teaching in Hong Kong,
Hayhoe said.
</P>
<P>
All students are therefore required to take 60-hour language
course each in Chinese, English and Putonghua (standard Chinese)
and to meet relevant language benchmarks before graduation, she
added.
</P>
<P>
The program also encourages the use of computers as tools for
learning in primary schools to ensure that students will develop
efficient basic computer skills and are introduced to issues in
information technology, Hayhoe said.
</P>
<P>
All students would need to demonstrate a basic level of
computer competence prior to taking a module on Computer Assisted
Learning in the final year, she said.
</P>
<P>
Special attention has also been given to the provision of civic
and moral education in the program, Hayhoe stressed.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to prepare graduate primary teachers who will
demonstrate sound academic and professional performance in the
process of developing all-round young school learners as committed
members of the Hong Kong community, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
