<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photographs of Buddhist Remains Exhibited in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition focusing on
Buddhist relics of the period when the Khitan people of the Liao
Dynasty (916-1125) and the Jurchens of the Jin Dynasty
(1115-1234) made the Beijing area their capital opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
All the photographs were the results of a five-year joint
exploration of Beijing's history by Japanese scholar Virginia
Fumiyo Anami and German professional photographer Kosima Weber Liu.
</P>
<P>
Anami, a scholar of East Asian history, lived for many years in
Beijing and has written numerous articles on Beijing's history and
Buddhism. Liu studied art history at the Central Academy of Fine
Arts in Beijing, and has been living in Beijing since 1984.
</P>
<P>
This collection of photographs illustrates what remains of the
Liao-Jin period and includes stories from that history.
</P>
<P>
The Liao called Beijing Nanjing or Yanjing from the year 938;
the Jurchens captured the Liao capital in 1122 and made
it their capital, calling it Zhongdu, or central capital in 1153.
</P>
<P>
During this time Buddhism flourished, and even today the
remaining Liao and Jin temples, pagodas, stone carvings and even
ancient trees are still redolent of this 1,000-year cultural
heritage.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Liao/Jin City Wall Museum, where the exhibition is
being held, straddles the ancient Jin city wall's water gate and
is a replica of the original structure.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that these photographs are of high value in
both artistic and academic terms. They also hope that, while
entertaining the viewers, the exhibition will help to enhance
their sense of cultural relics protection, as advocated by the two
photographers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
