<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outcome of Guangzhou Trade Fair Better Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The curtain fell today on the
83rd China Export Commodities Fair in this capital of Guangdong
Province in south China, after a record 10.2 billion US
dollars-worth of export transactions had been completed.
</P>
<P>
"The final results of the trade fair surprised market
observers," said Liu Shanzai, vice-minister of foreign trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Regarded as a "thermometer" of China's foreign trade, the
biannual event this time had attracted about 65,000 overseas
buyers from 166 countries and regions since it opened on April 15.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the impact of the East Asian financial crisis,
however, orders from Asian countries like Singapore, Malaysia,
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea dropped considerably this year
as expected.
</P>
<P>
But China's business volumes with the European Union, the United
States, the Middle East, Latin America, Africa and Eastern Europe
have been increasing sharply.
</P>
<P>
Europe and the United States remain the top two markets for
Chinese exporters this year, with the trade volumes with the two
markets increasing by eight percent and 10 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Overseas buyers still favor Chinese export products, as they
can find whatever they need, said Hamoudi Youssef, a businessman
from the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Name-brand products and commodities with high added value sell
well at the Guangzhou trade fair. The Zhuhai Green Group, based in
Zhuhai City, Guangdong, received orders worth 150 million US
dollars for its electrical appliances at the fair.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xiangdong, assistant minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, said that the optimistic trend observed at the fair
has enhanced his conviction that China's exports will grow by more
than 10 percent and hit the 200-billion-US-dollar target soon.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
