<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Airlines, Hang Seng Bank Winners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Airlines was voted
Asia's Most Admired Company for a fifth time in seven years while
Hang Seng Bank emerged biggest winner as a new entrant in an
annual survey to identify Asia's Most admired Companies (AMAC).
</P>
<P>
Singapore Airlines was also voted Top Airline in the Asian
Business survey which covers 250 local, regional and multinational
companies in 10 broad industry sectors.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong-based Hang Seng Bank was voted Top Bank/ Finance
Company and the Most Honest and Ethical Company, according to the
results of the poll announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the severe problems brought about by the financial
crisis in the Republic of Korea, the country's Hotel Shilla was
voted Top Hotel/ Leisure Company and Pohang Iron &AMP; Steel was voted
the Company Best Able to Cope with Regional Economic Instability
and the Company Making the Greatest Contribution to the Local
Economy.
</P>
<P>
The votes for the Company with the Greatest Potential for
Growth and Greatest Potential for Future Profits went to Taiwan
Semiconductor Manufacturing Co., which also won the Best Employer
award.
</P>
<P>
The awards for Highest Quality of Products/ Services went to
Sony Corp of Japan, which was the second in overall rankings.
</P>
<P>
Hewlett Packard of the United States stood at the third place
in overall rankings, the highest among North American companies.
</P>
<P>
At the top 20 table, San Miguel Corporation, last year's
runner-up in overall rankings, plunged to the 14th place this
year.
</P>
<P>
Asian Business Executive Editor James Leung said the results of
the survey have convinced the fact that branding is crucial to a
company's success, especially during bad times.
</P>
<P>
Asian Business is a monthly magazine aimed at the business
community across Asia. The poll, conducted by an independent
research company, was first launched in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The companies selected for the survey include the largest
listed companies, by turnover, in nine Asian countries and
regions, plus a variety of high-visibility Western multinationals
and a few Chinese firms.
</P>
<P>
Questionnaires were sent to 9,000 senior executives, chief
executive officers, and company board members on a random basis.
Close to 2,000 replies were received. 
</P>
</TEXT>
