<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upgrading Standards to Improve HK's Medical Profession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Academy of
Medicine (HKAM) has recently approved six additional specialities,
which it seeks to be included in the Specialist Register by the
Hong Kong Medical Council.
</P>
<P>
HKAM's leading doctors believed that the move will upgrade the
standard of Hong Kong's medical care.
</P>
<P>
The Special Register, launched and gazetted last month in Hong
Kong offers the community direct access and information on
qualified doctors that have been recognized by the Medical Council
as specialists.
</P>
<P>
"The Specialist Register in Hong Kong is a clear indication of
the high standards that are currently developed in the medical
profession to cater for the needs of the community," said David
Fang, HKAM's president.
</P>
<P>
The six new specialities brought the existing Register-covered
specialties to a total of 42.
</P>
<P>
To be recommended for inclusion in the Register, candidates
must satisfy the Academy that they have fulfilled the requirements
for training and obtained the necessary higher qualifications.
</P>
<P>
Around 2,000 specialists, all Fellows of the HKAM, were
included in the Register on the first round of application in
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Doctors must have at least six years of recognized structured
specialist training and pass an exit/assessment of the Academy in
the related speciality before they can be admitted as a Fellow of
the HKAM for inclusion in the specialist Register.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurated in December 1993, the HKAM is an independent
institution with statutory power to organize, monitor, asses and
accredit all postgraduate medical training and to oversee the
provision of continuing medical education. It enables Hong Kong
doctors, having completed recognized specialist training to become
specialists registered by the Medical Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
