<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The diminishing likelihood of a
cut in interest rates bolstered the Australian dollar Thursday,
pushing it higher to close above 65.00 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The unit ended the local session on its highs for the day at
65.22 U.S. cents from 64.77 previously.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank senior foreign exchange dealer Nick
Volanakis said stronger than expected wages data released Thursday
had wiped the chances of a cut in official interest rates by the
Reserve Bank of Australia off the agenda in the near term.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the figures took a bit of the heat out of the
expectation of an interest rate cut," Volanakis said.
</P>
<P>
Average weekly ordinary time earnings (AWOTE) figures for the
February quarter released by the Australian Bureau of Statistics
showed full-time adult AWOTE climbed by 1.3 percent in the three
months to February to a seasonally adjusted 720.30 Australian
dollars. Over the year, AWOTE were an adjusted 3.9 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that although higher than expected, the data
were still in line with Reserve Bank of Australia targets.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing with the AWOTE figure is that the annual
rate is still below 4.0 percent," Axiom Funds Management senior
economist Matthew Drennan said.
</P>
<P>
"So while it is a little higher than expectations would have
suggested, I think it is still quite comfortably in line with
Reserve Bank targets and certainly shouldn't provide any great
source of inflationary pressure over the next 12 months."
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading, the Australian dollar ended at 85.98
from 85.68 against Japanese yen and at 1.1678 from 1.1628 against
Deutsche marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
