<HEADLINE> Chubais Becomes Head of Russian Power Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Sacked Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Anatoly Chubais has been appointed chief executive of the
state-controlled Unified Energy Systems (UES) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Sannikov, an official of the Russian Ministry of Fuel
and Energy and a UES board member, said Chubais is expected
to ease the company's debt problem.
</P>
<P>
The UES, one of the monopolies in the transport, of natural gas
and energy sector, is owed some 2 billion U.S. dollars by Russian
factories and industries, and other CIS countries, who cannot
afford to pay their debts.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government holds 52.7 percent of shares in the
nation's electric sector, as well as direct stakes in most
regional utilities.
</P>
<P>
The 42-year-old Chubais was sacked when Russian President Boris
Yeltsin fired the government on March 23. 
</P>
