<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms Lead Xiamen Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen's foreign investment has
witnessed big growth over the past 17 years and currently
accounts for the lion's share of the local economy, according to
Shi Zhaobin, secretary of the Xiamen Committee of the Communist
Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises accounted for 80 percent of the
city's total 1997 industrial output value and contributed close to
33 percent of the local tax revenues, according to Shi.
</P>
<P>
He said the port city has approved 4,343 foreign-funded
projects involving total contracted investments of 13.76 billion
US dollars, including allocated funds of over 7.97 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 68.8 percent of foreign-funded projects are closely
related to the manufacturing sector. The investment in the service
sector and agriculture sector accounted for 29 percent and 2.2
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The influx of foreign investments has led to radical changes in
the city economic structure, with the ratio for the agricultural
sector falling from 21.67 percent in 1980 to 6.03 percent
in 1997, said Shi.
</P>
<P>
He added that the ratio for the industrial sector fell
slightly, while that for the service sector rose from 21.49
percent in 1980 to 42.49 percent in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
