<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Around 70 percent of top-class
sportsmen are cheating with drugs, former British athletic star
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Yates, a former European 1,500 meters indoor champion,
and Britain's former 400 meters runner Derek Redmond said they
believed most athletes who appeared in a final at the top level
were taking banned substances.
</P>
<P>
"Once you get down to a final, you are looking at eight to 15
people and you are looking seriously at 70 percent (of them
cheating with drugs)," Yates said in a debate about drugs in sport
on BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
"I have heard that figure and I wouldn't be surprised. It is
going on in the world of athletics. There is hypocrisy from guys
who say 'don't do drugs' and they are on drugs," Redmond
continuted.
</P>
<P>
The issue of drug abuse has been thrust into the spotlight
again because of a doping scandal involving Ireland's Olympic
champion Michelle de Bruin, who is being investigated for
allegedly tampering with a doping sample.  
