<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Chinese Trade Unions Adjust Role to Changing Times(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- As China's economic reforms cut
deeper, trade unions across the country are making every effort to
shift their function from prompting workers to toil harder for the
state to safeguarding workers' rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
"It should be the bound duty of trade unions to protect the
workers, who are both the unions' founders and members," said an
official with the All-China Federation of Trade Unions
(ACFTU). "But in the past, we used to lay more emphasis on
encouraging and prompting the workers to make greater
contributions to their country."
</P>
<P>
In the time of a planned economy, all workers labored for, and
were protected by, the state. There were no labor-capital
conflicts in the enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, with the establishment in recent years of a socialist
market economy which allows the co-existence of multiple ownership
systems, many Chinese workers are no longer directly patronized by
the government in terms of employment and pay.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, as a result of the separation of government functions
from enterprise operation, Chinese businesses have gained
increasing autonomy, which has led to infringement on the workers'
interests and rights.
</P>
<P>
In some state-owned enterprises that have turned to the
shareholding system in a bid to overcome economic difficulties,
all workers were forced to buy shares. In other places, mergers or
sales of state enterprises were announced without approval by
workers' congresses, which according to law should have the right
of supervision.
</P>
<P>
The number of labor-capital disputes in private, foreign-funded
and township enterprises has also been surging in recent
years. Statistics from the ACFTU put the total number of labor
disputes in China last year at more than 71,000, more than double
the figure in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In a recent editorial, Workers' Daily, a major national
newspaper based in Beijing, warned: "The greatest danger presently
threatening the trade unions' development and even survival is
that they have lost their close relationship with the broad masses
of the workers."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
