<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Foreign Minister Returns Home from New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 30 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahaf returned home from New York on Thursday after
attending U.N. Security Council meetings on arms inspections
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in New York, al-Sahaf held talks with
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and met with representatives of
the Security Council member states.
</P>
<P>
He repeated a longtime Iraqi claim that his country has
implemented relevant U.N. resolutions on dismantling weapons of
mass destruction, and demanded lifting the seven-year-old
U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq
(UNSCOM) said in its report submitted to the Security Council that
it had made "virtually no progress" over the last six months in
verifying Iraq's compliance with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The report led to a Monday U.N. decision to prolong economic
sanctions against Iraq. U.N. arms inspectors must certify that
Iraq has destroyed all banned weapons before the council lifts
the embargo imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Describing the decision as "very disappointing," al-Sahaf
pledged to cooperate with the Security Council to refute "lies and
fallacies" included in the UNSCOM's report that Iraq is still
holding banned arms.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the purpose behind such lies and
allegations was to justify aggressive U.S. and British policies
against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahaf was accompanied by Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rasheed,
the top Iraqi negotiator in talks with the UNSCOM during the
U.N. deliberation held in New York.
</P>
<P>
The review was the first since Iraq signed a deal last February
with Annan to open all sites, including presidential compounds to
U.N. arms inspectors. The agreement has avoided a U.S.-led military
strike against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Chinese Trade Unions Adjust Role to Changing Times(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Wang Chidong, deputy head of the grassroots work
department of the ACFTU, the new circumstances are pressing the
Chinese trade unions to make historic changes and assume the
responsibility of protecting all workers' legal rights and
interests.
</P>
<P>
He said that, at present, the most important tasks for trade
unions in China include promoting the establishment of the
workers' congress system, signing collective labor contracts with
the enterprises on behalf of the workers, and assisting local
governments in finding new jobs for the laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
To date, the workers' congress, which in accordance with the
law has the right to examine reform plans of the enterprise and
suggest the promotion or ouster of enterprise managers, has been
established in more than 300,000 businesses across China.
</P>
<P>
But an ACFTU official acknowledged that in many places the
power of the workers' congress has been largely neglected and all
major issues concerning enterprise operations were decided by a
few people in management.
</P>
<P>
Many enterprise owners also used various excuses to avoid or
delay the signing of a collective labor contract with the workers,
he added.
</P>
<P>
With further reforms in state-owned enterprises, more than 11
million Chinese workers have now been laid off, and the figure is
expected to continue rising this year.
</P>
<P>
Qin Yangong, deputy head of the social protection department
with the ACFTU, said that by the end of last year trade unions
across the country had raised 2 billion yuan (250 million
U.S. dollars) in relief funds to help the laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions at all levels have also opened a large number of
vocational training or job placement centers for the laid-off
workers, and have directly offered more than 700,000 jobs in
union-run businesses to these workers, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
