<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legislature Announces Mass Discussion on Law Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature announced
plans to make public a draft of amendments to the Land-Use Law to
solicit people's opinions.
</P>
<P>
"The draft of the revised Land-Use Law will affect agriculture,
the immediate interests of 900 million farmers and our coming
generations," said Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), at the closing meeting
of the second session of the committee which ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By publicizing the draft and hearing the response, the highest
legislative body can collect more opinions from the public and
improve the law, Li said.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, the state must adopt special policies
to protect farmland resources, and strictly prevent farmland from
being transferred into other uses.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it strictly controls the different uses of
agricultural, construction and idle land. The draft, regarded as
an overhaul of the current law, controls urban landscaping as well.
</P>
<P>
China adopted land-use legislation in 1986. However, the
existing law is considered unsuitable for a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Considering the effects of the amendments, the NPC Standing
Committee unanimously approved the mass discussion of the draft
law.
</P>
<P>
It decided to publicize the draft of amendments to the
Constitution in 1982 for people's discussion. After that, the
Standing Committee also released drafts of Administrative
Procedure Law, the Basic Law of Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region and the Basic Law of Macao Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Chairman Li said that public discussion might
increase people's legal understanding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
