<HEADLINE> China Expands Protection of Ocean Ecology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese environmental
protection official said today that China will improve the
management of the ocean's ecology in an attempt to prevent red
tides.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Natural Protection Department of the State
Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA) said that China
will increase spending on wastewater treatment facilities in
coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
"The control over the development of seacoast and marshes will
be tightened to protect the coastal ecology," he said.
</P>
<P>
The official added that China will improve environmental
management of agriculture as soon as possible and strictly control
the density of aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
The red tides which have plagued coastal waters in south
China's Guangdong Province and Hong Kong has caused losses of 350
million yuan, including losses of 50 million yuan in Guangdong,
according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
SEPA said that pollution has contributed to red tides, adding
that huge land-originated pollution and unscientific aquaculture
are two outstanding problems.
</P>
<P>
China empties eight billion tons of wastewater into the sea
annually, with the volume increasing yearly. In addition, overly
dense aquaculture has also contributed to pollution
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
