<HEADLINE> South Africa to Launch Anti-Flu Vaccination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's health
departments have called on people in the country to have
vaccination against looming winter flu so as to boost their
immunity against the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to Tony Brewitt, Chief Executive Officer of
Medicross Family Medical Centers, such vaccinations should
ideally take place in May as the "protective effects of the
treatment develop some 114 days later".
</P>
<P>
Brewitt said flu is a contagious respiratory disease caused by
a virus. "While it cannot be completely cured, it can be
prevented by vaccination which has been shown to offer 80 to 90
percent protection in healthy young individuals.
</P>
<P>
"For most healthy people, flu is mild to moderately severe
illness, but for those in high risk categories, it can be life
threatening. Complications can be serious, even in healthy young
individuals," he said.
</P>
<P>
Complications include inflammation of the heart muscle
following vigorous exercise. Influenza often triggers other
diseases like ear infections, sinusitis and meningitis, medical
experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
