<HEADLINE> Tunisian, Jordanian Leaders Hold Talks on Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Tunisian President Zine Al-Abidine
Ben Ali held talks Wednesday night with visiting King Hussein of
Jordan on bilateral ties, as well as Arab, regional and
international issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Tunis Afrique Presse quoted an official spokesman for the
Tunisian Presidency as saying that the two leaders expressed their
satisfaction at the outcome of Tunisian-Jordanian cooperation in
all fields, especially in the economic one.
</P>
<P>
The two countries recently agreed to set up a joint free trade
zone and reactivate the role of the private sector in promoting
investment enterprises and partnership.
</P>
<P>
The two leader also affirmed the Tunisian-Jordanian Joint
Commission meetings, which meet regularly, should continue so as
to bring bilateral cooperation to the highest level.
</P>
<P>
The talks also dealt with the Middle East peace process and the
efforts made by both countries and the international community
designed to save the peace process from its current deadlock, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian president reiterated his country's attitude
supporting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the efforts being made to ease the
suffering of the Iraqi and Libyan peoples as a result of the
U.N. embargoes. King Hussein reiterated his suggestion that Iraq
and the U.S. enter into direct dialog.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were laid on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed air and arms embargoes on
Libya in 1992 after Libya refused to surrender for trial in
Britain or the United States two Libyans accused of killing 270
people by blowing up a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two leaders underlined the necessity of
continuing efforts to clear the Arab atmosphere and reactivate
Arab joint action.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein arrived here Wednesday evening for a two-day
official visit to Tunisia within a tour of a number of Arab and
European countries. 
</P>
