<HEADLINE> Nigeria Urged to Exercise Restraint on Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The international society has
urged the Nigerian government to exercise restraint and not
execute the six persons sentenced to death by a special military
tribunal for alleged coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said Wednesday what
Nigeria needs at the moment is genuine national reconciliation
rather than blood-letting.
</P>
<P>
A special bulletin from Mandela's office counseled Nigeria's
Head of State, General Sani Abacha, to realize that death
sentences are no longer fashionable in the world today as many
countries have expunged them from their statute books.
</P>
<P>
Also reacting to the verdict, Commonwealth Secretary-General
Emeka Anyaoku urged the Nigerian government "to exercise utmost
restraint and humanitarianism over the death sentences."
</P>
<P>
The British government, according to a British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC) report, urged Nigeria to respect the human
rights of the condemned by giving them the right to appeal
against their sentences.
</P>
<P>
A special military tribunal Tuesday sentenced to death former
Chief of General Staff Oladipo Diya and five
others on charges of treason. Ten others were sentenced to jail
terms ranging from 14 years to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The sentences are to be approved by the Provisional Ruling
Council, the highest decision-making body in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Noted individuals and groups in Nigeria have also appealed to
the government to temper justice with mercy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
