<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-President Reaffirms Stability of Chinese Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHEJU, South Korea, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President
Hu Jintao reaffirmed here Thursday the significance to stabilize
the Chinese yuan (Renminbi) in the wake of the Southeast Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's firm commitment not to devaluate
Renminbi is a serious and well-based one made before the
international community, Hu told reporters before flying home.
</P>
<P>
To elaborate his answers to media questions, Hu said that
firstly, China's economy is showing a trend of high growth and low
inflation, which serves as a strong basis for the stable Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, he said, China has been running a favorable balance
of international payments, with a steady growth of its foreign
exchange reserves now exceeding 140 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the total amount and structure of the country's
external debts are relatively rational, and that the pressure on
its foreign debt payment has not been great, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, although keeping Renminbi at its current value has a
negative impact on exports, he said, low labor costs have made
some Chinese commodities still competitive on the world market.
</P>
<P>
Lastly, the vice-president explained, the restructuring of
China's financial system is proceeding in an orderly way and the
supervision and control over the financial sector will be further
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Based on these evaluations, Hu said, the Chinese government is
fully confident that the value of Renminbi will stay where it is.
</P>
<P>
Such a monetary policy on the part of China will boost the
stability and growth of the home economy, as well as contribute to
the stabilization of the Asian economy as a whole and to the
strengthening of market confidence.
</P>
<P>
Hu left here for home later in the day after concluding a
five-day official visit to South Korea. South Korea was the
second leg of Hu's East Asian tour which also took him to Japan.
</P>
<P>
It was Hu's first foreign trip since he was elected
vice-president in March. During the visit, Hu held talks with
South Korean leaders, including President Kim Dae-jung and acting
Prime Minister Kim Jong-pil, to discuss issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Hu is also a member of the Political Bureau Standing Committee
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
