<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Visits China College for Judges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said today that she hoped U.S.-China
cooperation in the field of law can be expanded.
</P>
<P>
Albright made her remarks here before an audience of more than
100 judges attending a course at the China National Judges College
under the Supreme People's Court, which is an adult education
college for the training of senior judges.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that she is aware that in recent years China has
made a major effort to reform and develop its legal system, and
that the United States is very interested in the "important legal
development" that is taking place in China.
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that the Chinese leadership and people
recognize the "need to strengthen the rule of law and to ensure
its judicial system is fair to all Chinese," adding that this is
"essential to cope with the vast economic and social changes that
are now occurring in China."
</P>
<P>
"The college demonstrates the commitment China is making to
further develop its legal system," added Albright.
</P>
<P>
She said that during the summit meeting last year in the United
States, Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill
Clinton agreed to launch a new initiative to cooperate in the
field of law, which she said is in the interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Observing that the legal communities of both countries are
enthusiastic about the initiative, Albright said she hoped that
the college would be a partner in bilateral exchanges and
cooperation in the field of law. 
</P>
