<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Govt Wants Genocide Criminals Extradited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government is trying
for the extradition of the genocide criminals holed up in some
west African states, a senior government official told the Rwanda
News Agency (RNA).
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to do everything possible in order to have them
(genocide criminals) extradited to Rwanda," said Faustin
Nteziryayo, Rwandan Minister of Justice, during a telephone
interview with RNA.
</P>
<P>
Nteziryayo's statement came shortly after the announcement of
the arrest of the former Prefect of Butare, Colonel Alphonse
Nteziryayo, in Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
Two other Rwandan nationals, Laurent Serubuga and Francois
Sibomana, were also said to have been put under house arrest in
neighbouring Mali, pending a request by the Rwandan government or
the International Criminal Tribunal to have them extradited.
</P>
<P>
Both Mali and Burkina Faso have declared that they have no
extradition treaty with the Rwandan government, hinting that the
criminals might be transferred to Arusha International Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
"Here the question of extradition treaty does not really apply
for genocide crimes and crimes against humanity," said
Nteziryayo. "These countries should abide by the 1948 convention
which requests all governments to arrest and extradite genocide
criminals," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said, "This issue of Rwandan criminals roaming in many
countries without any fear for being arrested will be raised
during a meeting that Kofi Annan, and officials from the
International Criminal Tribunal will hold with Rwandan
authorities in Kigali."
</P>
<P>
Most of these criminals have been arrested on the basis of a
list issued by the Rwandan government which features about 2,000
most wanted criminals made of masterminds and organisers of the
1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
"This list is being reviewed and updated," since some
information was lacking as well as new names will be added,
Nteziryayo said.
</P>
<P>
The 1994 genocide in Rwanda left over 500,000 people dead in
less than three months.
</P>
<P>
According to some scientists, the methods used here to
slaughter Tutsis and opposition Hutus were eight times faster
than the gas chambers of the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, over 130,000 genocide suspects are detained in
Rwandan prisons, waiting for trials. Last year, about 300
suspects were tried by Rwandan war crimes tribunals.
</P>
<P>
The first 22 genocide criminals sentenced to death were
publicly executed last Friday in five different locations of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
