<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Education Network to Cover Sub-Saharan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 30 (Xinhua) - Helped by the World Bank, a
satellite distance education network, known as the African
Virtual University (AVU), will launch four undergraduate degree
programs for the Sub-Saharan African countries next year.
</P>
<P>
Local media Thursday quoted Professor Beda Mutagahywa, the
Director of the Computing Centre of the University of Dar es
Salaam (UDSM), as saying that the AVU will run computer Science,
computer engineering, electric engineering and nursing degree
courses.
</P>
<P>
The AVU will enroll its own students for the programs under
private basis at 12 receiving sites in six Anglophone countries,
Tanzania, Kenya, Ethiopia, Uganda, Ghana and Zimbabwe,
Mutaagahywa said.
</P>
<P>
He said that AVU is designed to offer undergraduate degree
programs of televised instructions from the United States and
Ireland to train a large number of African scientists,
technicians, engineers, business managers and employees.
</P>
<P>
"It also aims at providing an academic environment in which
African educational institutions and students can participate
effectively in the worldwide community of learning, research and
dissemination of knowledge,"he added.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the sites are at the UDSM and the Tanzania Open
University. In Kenya, at Kenyatta University and in Uganda at
Makerere University, Kyambogo Polytechnic and Martyrs University.
</P>
<P>
Mutagahywa said the AVU project is implemented in three
phases. As a pilot, the first phase started on February 26 this
year in UDSM to comprise seminars and short courses to the
would-be students.
</P>
<P>
He said that several basic equipment, provided by the World
Bank, have been stationed in the UDSM including one satellite
dish and a lot of personal computers, video recorders, fax
machines and others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
