<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Progress Made in Intra-Afghan Talks Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia and
the rival Northern Alliance continued their peace talks Thursday
but no major progress was made in the morning session.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, assistant general secretary of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), told reporters after
the morning session that the two Afghan warring factions discussed
mainly the issues of lifting the blockade of humanitarian aid to
central Afghanistan and the release of POWs.
</P>
<P>
Bakar admitted that the progress in the morning session was
"slow." There are still some differences between the two sides on
certain issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the holding of the next round of intra-Afghan
peace talks, Bakar said that the matter has not been discussed so
far.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there are a number of countries which have
offered to host the next round of meeting.
</P>
<P>
Taliban representative to Pakistan Abdul Hakeem told reporters
that "we want an early formation of the Ulema (religious scholars)
Commission. And it is the Ulema Commission that should discuss the
matters relating to ceasefire and release of POWs."
</P>
<P>
However, Hakeem said the Northern Alliance insists that these
issues should be discussed by the Joint Steering Committee, which
consists of five Taliban and nine alliance representatives.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the Taliban and the Northern Alliance on
Thursday morning lasted for more than three hours. The two sides
are to resume their talks at 03:00 p.m. Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In their talks Wednesday, the two Afghan warring factions
reached a three-point agreement: each side will submit a list of
Ulema for the commission; neither side will have the right to veto
any names on the proposed list; and the deliberations and
decisions should be completed and implemented in accordance with
the principles of Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
Thursday was the fifth day since the Taliban and the Northern
Alliance opened their peace talks on Sunday. As previously-agreed
by the two sides, the ongoing intra-Afghan peace talks are to be
concluded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the divergence of opinion on certain important issues, the
Taliban and the rival Northern Alliance are not expected to make
any major breakthrough before the end of the current round of
peace talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
