<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call on Control Spread of Harmful Seaweed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese oceanographers have
warned relevant government departments to take measures to prevent
the spread of a dangerous seaweed into the Chinese coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
So-called "Super Seaweed" easily adapts to the marine
environment. It grows vigorously, absorbing vast amounts
of sunlight, oxygen and nutrients.
</P>
<P>
The vigorous growth of the seaweed most often decimates the
fish, shrimp and shellfish populations and destroys coral beds.
</P>
<P>
"Super Seaweed has wreaked havoc with the fishing operations
and the environments of many countries," said an expert
with the National Oceanographic Bureau (NOB).
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that immediate steps should be taken
to expand research into methods of reducing the damage caused by
this plant, as well as effective measures to eradicate it. The rapid
spread of Super Seaweed results from the fact that the plant grows
on the hulls of vessels which regularly ply the world's oceans.
</P>
<P>
The NOB says that the plant has not as yet been found in
China's sea areas, but stress that the possibility of its
appearance in the Chinese waters exists because a large number of
ships enter into the nation's ports.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has organized experts to conduct research on the
plant, and has informed the Customs, ports and quarantine stations
to adopt appropriate measures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0182 </DOCNO>
