<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President on Korean Peninsula Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHEJU, SOUTH KOREA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The overall situation
on the Korean peninsula is generally easing up, Chinese
Vice-President Hu Jintao said here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Meeting the press before ending his official South Korea tour,
Hu said China welcomes the recent expression of willingness by
both sides on the peninsula to improve their ties.
</P>
<P>
As a neighbor of the Korean peninsula, China, as always, has
been pursuing the maintenance of peace and stability there as its
fundamental principle in handling affairs in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to further its constructive efforts for that
end, the Chinese vice-president said, adding that the issue of the
peninsula is mainly that of the two sides on the south and north.
</P>
<P>
Hu hoped the two sides, by dialogues and consultations, would
deepen mutual understanding, expand mutual trust and improve their
relations, so as to facilitate peaceful reunification in the end.
</P>
<P>
China has been actively backing and participating in the
four-party talks among China, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK), South Korea and the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
To build a mechanism of permanent peace on the Korean
peninsula, Hu said, China is ready to work with the other three
parties to push the talks ahead toward progresses.
</P>
<P>
During the news conference held prior to his flying home, he
also answered questions about the stability of the Chinese
currency, China's environment protection efforts and other
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
