<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Launches Largest Operation Against Kurdish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish government troops are
carrying on a military operation against the Kurdish rebels in
eastern and southeastern Turkey, the largest over the past 14
years, Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
General Nahit Snogul, head of 24 army generals commanding the
mission, was quoted by the paper as saying at a press conference
late Wednesday in the southeastern province of Bingol that about
40,000 Turkish troops participated in the military action
codenamed "Murat" starting from April 25.
</P>
<P>
In respect of the size of battlefield and level of
participation, the operation is the largest of its kind since the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) began guerilla warfares in
the region since 1984, Snogul said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five days, a total of 35 PKK members were killed
by Turkish government troops and three army soldiers died during
the fightings as well.
</P>
<P>
Some PKK rebels have been surrounded in a triangular area
between provinces of Bingol and Diyarbakir by the government
troops, according to Snogul.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the militants to surrender, Snogul said that "we
don't want anyone to die, even though they are terrorists." He
promised that they would be treated in a humanitarian manner if
they lay down their arms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the commander also denied press reports that Sedin
Sakik, a former senior member of the PKK who was captured two
weeks ago by Turkish security authorities in northern Iraq, had
anything to do with the military operation.
</P>
<P>
The operation was launched in accordance with a plan worked
out by Turkish General Staff in February, Snogul said.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts, however, believe that Sakik most probably
provided some useful information to the Turkish military regarding
the deployment of the PKK forces in the mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, there are around 4,800 PKK
militants involved in the anti-government war, 2,300 in eastern
and southeastern Turkey and 2,500 in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old bloody war against the
Turkish government in an attempt to establish an independent
Kurdish state in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 35,000 rebels, soldiers and civilians were killed in
the armed clashes between government troops and the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
