<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets U.S. Secretary Of State (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, in a
meeting here today with visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, said that he believes President Clinton's upcoming visit
to China will further the development of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the Chinese government places great importance on
President Clinton's state visit to China in June, which is another
major event in Sino-American relations after Chinese President
Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his conviction that, with joint effort and
conscientious preparation on both sides, President Clinton's visit
would be a great success.
</P>
<P>
Albright, while emphasizing the importance of the U.S.-China
relationship, said that the American side is delighted to see the
opportunities for the United States and China to develop
cooperation in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
She said President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States
last fall demonstrated the depth of the development of the
U.S.-China relationship. She said the U.S. side expects President
Clinton's visit to further consolidate relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed appreciation and gratitude for China's
stabilizing role during the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said China, while closely following the development of this
financial crisis, has promised not to devalue its currency and has
provided assistance to affected countries within its capability
through bilateral and multilateral channels, although its own
economy has also been affected by the crisis, with further
consequences possible.
</P>
<P>
"All this constitutes China's positive contributions to
safeguarding regional stability and proves that China is a
responsible big country," Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
