<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Arrives in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
arrived in Israel on Thursday to attend the activities of Israel's
50th anniversary of its founding at the invitation of the
Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Gore was greeted at the Ben Gurion Airport by
Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Gore is scheduled to attend the "Jubilee Bells" event at
Givat Ram Stadium here Thursday evening, which will be the major
anniversary event to be attended by Israeli government leaders
and thousands of local people.
</P>
<P>
Another important mission for Gore during his visit is to
try to help break the deadlock on the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Gore will meet with President Ezer Weizman Thursday and hold
official talks with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on this
issue Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon, Gore will leave Israel for an unannounced
destination, probably Egypt or Jordan, and will return to Israel
Saturday evening. Shortly after his return, Gore will hold talks
in the West Bank city of Ramallah with Yasser Arafat, President of
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Paletinian peace talks have been stalled for over a
year due to Israel's activities of building Jewish settlement
housing units on Har Homa in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock, high level meetings have been planned
between U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Netanyahu
and Arafat in London on May 4. The London meetings will discuss
the U.S. new proposal for bringing the Mideast peace process
back on track.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal, which has not been made public so far, is to
ask Israel to conduct a 13.1 percent troop redeployment in the
West Bank, to ask Israel to have a "time out" for settlement
activities, and to ask both sides to work out ways for security
cooperation and the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross returned to the region on Sunday to
try to lay the grounds for the London talks, but his mission has
achieved no progress so far although he held several rounds of
talks with the Israelis and Palestinians during his shuttle
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli troop redeployment, Arafat openly stated on
Wednesday in Gaza that he accepts the U.S. 13.1 percent pullback
proposal, but Netanyahu has insisted that his government can not
hand that much land to the PNA during the next redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Whether Gore could succeed in urging Israel to accept the
U.S. proposal still remains uncertain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
