<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Egyptian newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has warned western
countries against harboring terrorists and granting them political
asylum.
</P>
<P>
In an interview released by the second channel of the French
television on Wednesday, Mubarak pointed out that unless European
countries and the United States give more attention to the issue,
the plague of terrorism would sweep the whole world.
</P>
<P>
Al-Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa returned home after
ending a two-day visit to Gaza, where he briefed Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat a meeting between Mubarak and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Cairo Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has advised Netanyahu to accept a U.S.-proposed plan on
Israel's withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the West Bank. Netanyahu
rejected the suggestion, and instead demanded Mubarak to exert
influence on Palestinians to make more concessions.
</P>
<P>
Al Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian and U.S. officials expected a scheduled visit by
U.S. Vice President Al Gore to Cairo next Sunday will give a new
impetus towards the promotion of the relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Gore is to hold talks with Mubarak and their discussions will
focus on developing economic cooperation between Cairo and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Gore's two-day visit to Egypt falls within the context of a
regional tour which will also take him to Saudi Arabian and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Minister of Economy Youssef Butrous Ghali said on
Wednesday that operation of financial markets in Egypt was based
on full transparency, stressing the government would never allow
any manipulation at the stock exchange. 
</P>
