<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Releases 140 Detainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- About 140 detainees, including
some journalists, have been released in Nigeria on the orders of
the Head of State, General Sani Abacha, the New Nigerian reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, this is not in response to the list of 60 persons for
whom the Catholic Pontiff Pope John Paul II pleaded for clemency
during his visit to Nigeria last month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper quoted a reliable resource as saying
that the release should be seen as a most magnanimous gesture of
the Abacha regime, not induced by any local or international
pressure on the government.
</P>
<P>
Those released who are in four categories include those
convicted on various offences but who are over 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
They also include 10 convicted persons serving life
sentences but having already spent more than 10 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
Also released are journalists detained under Decree Two of the
government. The number of freed journalists is yet to be known.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth category are about 120 freed persons awaiting
trial for various offences.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha, in a nationwide broadcast to mark the
country's independence anniversary, promised on November 17, 1997
to release only those whose freedom would not undermine the peace
and stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper did not say when the detainees were freed. But
the release coincided with the sentence of accused coup plotters
including former No. 2 person Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya.
</P>
<P>
The special military tribunal Tuesday sentenced Diya and five
others, including two former ministers, to death.
</P>
<P>
In a quick response, Britain, the United States, South Africa
and the Commonwealth Wednesday faulted the trial, while
pro-democracy and human rights groups also launch a new round of
fire on the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
