<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200,000-Year-Old Stalagmite in Central China Insured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A stalagmite, which has growing
in a cave in central China for 200,000 years, has been insured for
100 million yuan (12 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This is the first natural landscape to be insured in China,
according to Ping'an Insurance Company, which holds the policy on
the stalagmite.
</P>
<P>
The 19.2-meter-high stalagmite is regarded as a symbolic scenic
spot of Huanglongdong Cave, or the Yellow Dragon Cave, in central
China's Hunan Province. The cave is home to more than 3,000
stalagmites.
</P>
<P>
"The stalagmite is wide in two ends and thin in the middle, and
there is a possibility of breakage," said Ye Wenzhi, an executive
of Huanglongdong Tourism Investment Co. Ltd., the applicant. "The
symbolic stalagmite makes no small contribution to Huanglongdong's
30 million yuan annual income."
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, the insurance company should pay
damages caused by geological changes, fires, floods, storms or
lightning strikes. However, damage from earthquakes or human
activities are not covered.
</P>
<P>
"The premium rate is only five per 10,000, but the stalagmite
has grown for 200,000 years and we estimate that the risk of
damage is low," said an official with the insurance company.
</P>
<P>
Huanglongdong Tourism Investment Co. Ltd. said they want to
increase the protection awareness of the company's employees
through the insurance, at the same time building up the company's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
So far, the stalagmites and stalactites in the cave have been
put under special protection by the company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Issue Licences to More Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania plans to issue
licences to more insurance companies in the country to break the
monopoly of the National Insurance Corporation (NIC), local
newspapers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Crony Asukenye Kasamala, the Commissioner of Insurance in the
Ministry of Finance, said at a signing ceremony here
Wednesday that 27 companies have made inquiries of doing
insurance business in the east African country, and 10 of them
have collected application forms.
</P>
<P>
According to Kasamala, three have returned forms with
registration fees. The regulatory authorities are scrutinizing
the applications before issuing licences to them, he said, adding
that the process may take some two months.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement during the signing
ceremony of subscription and agreement between the Jubilee
Insurance Company (Tanzania) Limited and the Washington-based
International Finance Corporation (IFC).
</P>
<P>
Jubilee is a subsidiary of the Aga Khan Fund of Economic
Development (AKFED), which has a wide interest in tourism,
banking and industrial promotion services.
</P>
<P>
Officials with IFC, the wing of the World Bank that finances
private sector investments, said that Jubilee is likely to be the
first private insurance company to be approved in Tanzania since
the sector was liberalized last year.
</P>
<P>
IFC and AKFED respectively invested 285,000 US Dollars in the
Jubilee Insurance Company (Tanzania) Limited, which will provide
general, non-life insurance and also plans to offer life
insurance after one to two years.
</P>
<P>
Jubilee was operating in Tanzania during 1937 and 1967 until
insurance business was nationalized. At that time, the company
controlled about 30 to 40 percent of Tanzania's insurance market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
