<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Warns West Against Sheltering Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has warned that those Western countries giving shelter or
political asylum to terrorists will have the repercussions, the
English Daily Egyptian Gazette reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French TV Channel 2, broadcast
Wednesday night, Mubarak said that the terrorists would soon turn
on the countries that harbored them.
</P>
<P>
"Those terrorists have no loyalty to the countries that shelter
them exactly as they do not have towards their own countries," he
said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
The terrorists, the Egyptian leader added, served foreign
powers in Afghanistan and in other areas that seek to undermine
stability in Arab and Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
Unless the United States and the European countries are on full
alert, Mubarak warned, "the plague of terrorism will prevail the
world."
</P>
<P>
Muslim militants have been fighting a violent war against
Mubarak's secular government since 1992. After last November's
Luxor attack against foreign tourists, Cairo repeatedly demanded
Western countries including Britain to extradite leading Egyptian
terrorists known to be remote-controlling the insurgency back home.
</P>
<P>
About 1,300 people have been killed in the violence, which
mostly took place in the relatively less-developed Upper
Egypt. Fifty-eight foreign tourists were killed in the November
terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak ruled out dialog with Egyptian terrorist groups and
pledged more severe crackdown on them. He added that terrorists
used the dialog during the time of late President Anwar el Sadat
to expand their ranks.
</P>
<P>
Reconciliation talks had been conducted by Sadat's government
and the rebels before they gave way to more Muslim insurgency that
led to Sadat's assassination by militants in 1981.
</P>
<P>
"We had to take very strict measures within the law. Dialog
with terrorists was a big mistake that allowed them to beef up
their groups," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0209 </DOCNO>
