<HEADLINE> Waters in W. Uganda Contaminated with Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Rivers in the western Ugandan
districts of Bundibugyo and Bushenyi have been contaminated with
cholera germs , The New Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Cholera in those areas is spreading faster because some of
the rivers like Katerera in Bunyaruguru, Bushenyi, are infected,"
said Kenya Mugisha, program Manager of Control of Diarrhea
Diseases.
</P>
<P>
An early report said 20 people have died within three days in
Bundibugyo district in the west and another 600 patients are
still under treatment.
</P>
<P>
In Bushenyi, there were 11 deaths and 179 reported cases of
the disease since March 1.
</P>
<P>
Five districts in the west of the country bordering the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have been put on the alert due
the cholera outbreak in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Sam Okware, Chairman of the National Cholera Task Force, said
he had received cholera reports from Gulu district in the north,
Nebbi and Arua districts in the northwest, Hoima and Kibale
districts in the west. 
</P>
