<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Trade Union not Planning New Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) has said it is not planning another nationwide work
boycott, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, it will be seeking a mandate from workers on the next
course of action regarding their demands for the government to
scrap unpopular taxes and levies.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Tsvangirai, Secretary-General of the Labour Movement
that organized a national job stayaway on March 3 and 4 this
year, told a press conference Wednesday that the ZCTU also had no
intention of transforming itself into a political party that will
challenge the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union Patriotic
Front (ZANU-PF).
</P>
<P>
"There are rumours going round that the ZCTU will be
announcing a stayaway. We have not completed our consultations
and we will only announce a stayaway or no stayaway when we have
completed that exercise," he said, adding they will call a
special general council meeting on the way forward.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU wished to dispel rumours that the labour movement
would soon launch itself into a political party, Tsvangirai
noted.
</P>
<P>
"That is mischievous. If it is being discussed, it is not by
us because we are not thinking of forming a political party," he
said. 
