<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year inflation
has risen to a two-year high of 27.9 percent and is expected to
continue its upward trend in the coming months, Zimbabwe's
leading weekly ''Business'' reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Annual inflation rose from 24 percent in February to 27.9
percent in March, its highest level since January 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kongdom Financial Services Company's latest economic bulletin
said the sharp increase in inflation is a reflection of a rise in
food prices which rose 33.7 percent over the year to March 1998
compared to 24.1 percent in the year to February 1998.
</P>
<P>
Basic foodstuffs are growing at a particularly high rate and
in the 12 months to March 1998, prices of cooking oils and fats
rose by 54.9 percent, bread and other cereal based foodstuffs by
44 percent, coffee and tea by 43.2 percent while fruit and
vegatables rose by 42.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin said with fuel prices and electricity tariffs
expected to go up in the short term, the former by up to 30
percent, inflation was set to continue its upward trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
