<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Launches APEC Business Travel Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has launched the
APEC (Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation) Business Travel Card,
aimed at allowing easier movement of business people across
country borders, the Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Department of Foreign Affairs were quoted as
saying the automated system was being piloted at present between
member countries -- Australia, the Philippines and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The new card is aimed at providing approved business people
with the equivalent of visa-free travel privileges to
participating APEC economies.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, documents are to be processed under a
pre-clearance system that allows them to obtain multiple
short-term entry to all participating countries.
</P>
<P>
As a leading country for the system, Australia has developed
and provided the APEC Card Application System software for use by
five members -- the Philippines, Chile, China, Hong Kong and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The software will process national and foreign applications and
manage the exchange of data and information of applicants and
cardholders from among the five members.
</P>
<P>
APEC cardholders are able to use special immigration lanes and
pre-clearance granted for holders of APEC cards before arrival,
and they no longer need to stand in long queues at airports,
according to the Foreign Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
In Manila, applications for the card are now available at the
Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry (PCCI) and the
Philippine Exporters' Confederation (Philexport). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
