<HEADLINE> Moi to Chair Kenya's Economic Consultative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
is scheduled to chair an economic consultative meeting on May 6
in a bid to solve the current economic difficulties facing the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here on Wednesday, the president said
that he would name some eminent economists from within and
outside the government to prepare a paper to guide the
deliberations at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of all political parties, diplomatic missions,
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund were invited
to attend the consultative meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had held a meeting with the Development and
Democracy Group (DDG) representing 21 developed countries, and
the World Bank country director, during which he explained the
government's position on Kenya's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a forum on Kenya's economy was held in the port
city of Mombasa to seek ways for solving the country's economic
problems. The forum was sponsored by the World Bank, the United
States government and the German non-governmental organization of
Friedrich Ebert Stiftung.
</P>
<P>
President Moi criticized the forum for ignoring the existence
of a constitutionally elected government and accused the sponsors
of "having a hidden agenda and ulterior motives" against his
government.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that the Kenyan government should be
the central player in any discussions regarding the interests of
the country, noting that the World Bank had no genuine reason to
discuss Kenyan matters with shady non-governmental organizations.
</P>
