<HEADLINE> Tuberculosis Cases Increase Sharply in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- There has been an eightfold
increase of tuberculosis in Zimbabwe because of various factors
including overcrowding, malnutrition and high incidence of the
HIV virus which causes AIDS, The Herald daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
TB, which has been considered the disease of the past, has now
emerged as a major health threat. Now dubbed "the return of a
killer", TB was declared a global emergency last month.
</P>
<P>
The rapid increase of TB in Zimbabwe is related and attributed
to HIV infection. Studies in Zimbabwe have shown that more than
50 percent of tuberculosis cases were HIV-related.
</P>
<P>
During the past 10 years, said the report, TB cases rose from
5,848 in 1987 to 43,752 in 1997. The figures do not reflect the
true picture since not all TB cases are referred to the
government institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
