<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Propose Anti-Money-Laundering Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is to propose that the
European Union establishes a convention for cooperation in
fighting against criminal money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Justice and European Legal Integration Minister Vasil
Gotsev said at the opening of an international seminar on money
laundering that the idea behind the convention was to make the
non-judiciary bodies which engage in financial intelligence
exchange data on the origin and movement of dirty money.
</P>
<P>
He said dirty money comes from narcotics businesses,
international crime and prostitution. The uncovering of dirty
money that has already been legalized would be difficult, but in
the future the laundering of money will be just as hard.
</P>
<P>
Narcotics are the principal source of dirty money, European
experts attending the seminar said. The turnover of the global
narcotics business amounts to some 1,000 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and the other former socialist countries are
potentially endangered by investments by international criminal
cartels which in the 1980s used to invest their money mainly in
Latin America, said Interior Ministry Chief Secretary Bozhidar
Popov.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions for success involve legislative measures and
political will, which we already have, stopping the inflow of
dirty money, and breaking the rings for investing such money,"
Popov said.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank of Bulgaria would draft instructions for
banking employees to help in the detection of suspicious money
operations, Roumyana Georgieva of the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It is difficult to eliminate this type of crimes in Bulgaria
because a large number of the payments were made in cash,
Georgieva said.
</P>
<P>
The methods preferred by Bulgarian money launderers involve
investing in foreign assets, gambling and shops, said Deputy
Finance Minister Plamen Oresharski.
</P>
<P>
Oresharski predicted that in the future money launderers would
turn to the stock exchange. In the 1990s Bulgaria was one of the
countries where money laundering was flourishing, he stated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
