<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Jasper Ornament Unearthed in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Some beautifully designed jaspers
2,200 years old have been removed from a newly found tomb in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said one of the jaspers is the largest of its kind
ever found in China.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is located two kilometers from the north gate of the
city of Xi'an, capital of Shaanxi Province. Its occupant is a male
in his 40s, around whom experts found four jaspers and 12 jade
bars.
</P>
<P>
"The largest one has been smashed into 25 pieces and placed on
the head and belly of the tomb occupant," said an archeologist, who
explained that it was meant to ward off evil spirits.
</P>
<P>
After broken pieces were carefully reassembled, the jasper
regained its original appearance -- 43.2 centimeters in diameter,
round and flat in shape with a hole in the center. People can see
animal-masks, millet patterns and birds with phoenix heads and
snake-shaped bodies carved on the stone.
</P>
<P>
The tomb's occupant is believed to have been an official
guarding the emperor's treasure hall or a warrior during the Qin
Dynasty (221-206 B.C.) in accordance with a few characters carved
on jaspers and a large number of iron swords, arrowheads and
bronze crossbow triggers also found in the coffin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
