<HEADLINE> China Can Meet Market Demand for New Rockets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China's aerospace industry
has consistently developed new rockets in accordance with market
demand, according to today's Economic Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper explained that China has acquired a capacity to
develop high quality rockets.
</P>
<P>
China's Long March 3b rockets not only fully satisfy the
demands for placing geosynchronous in orbit, but also offer
certain technical advantages for the low- to medium-earth orbit
satellite market.
</P>
<P>
China has also developed a number of other rockets of the Long
March family, including Long March 2c/sd rockets with a 17 percent
launch success rate since 1975 and an upgraded model of the same
rocket which carried foreign manufactured satellites into orbit on
two separate occassions.
</P>
<P>
China has used the Long March Carrier Rocket to place
satellites in orbit since 1970, with an 88 percent success rate,
of 44 successful launches out of 50 attempts.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen launches have placed commercial satellites in orbit
for customers from a number of countries and regions, including
the United States, Sweden, Australia, Pakistan, the Philippines
and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
