<HEADLINE> More Foreign Investment Flows into Poland in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 29 (Xinhua) -- About 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign investments flowed into Poland in the first quarter of
this year, according to statistics from the Polish Foreign
Investment Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The figure means that foreign investment for the first half of
this year should exceed the 1.9 billion dollars in the first six
months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of March this year, the total amount of foreign
investment in the 1990s reached 22.1 billion U.S. dollars. The
bureau estimated that the number might reach 30 billion dollars by
the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper "Rzeczpospolita" reported Wednesday that there
was not much change on the structure of foreign investment. But
investment in the financial service sector slightly increased.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that more investment will flow into the
food processing and automobile industries in the near future.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Daewoo Group has invested one billion dollars in
Poland for automobile manufacturing and sales.
</P>
<P>
A report from "Gazeta Wyboreza" said the United States and
Germany were on the top of list of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts maintained that the direct cause for surge of
foreign investment in Poland was the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia. On top of that, Poland recently has better
performed economically than its neighbors such as Czech and
Hungary, and become more attractive to investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
