<HEADLINE> Gas Leakage Sealed, People Return Home in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- People who fled the neighborhood of
the Jalalabad gas field near Sylhet, northeast Bangladesh,
returned to their houses Wednesday after the gas leakage was
sealed, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Occidental, a U.S. company which has been
drilling the well, were quoted as saying that they would keep the
drilling suspended for a few days and "test" the well before
resuming drilling.
</P>
<P>
The Occidental had submitted a plan to kill the well and to
evaluate the cause of the incident to Petrobangla, the Bangladeshi
company in charge of gas and oil exploration in the country, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
An expert committee has been set up to probe the cause of the
leakage, and will report to the government within 15 days.
</P>
<P>
Panic gripped the neighborhood of the gas well Tuesday night
after large patches of gas were leaking out at the Jalalabad gas
field, making loud noise, and an alert was given by the local
government for people residing within one kilometer of the well to
evacuate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, workers of the Lakkatura and Malnichhara tea gardens
near the gas field staged strike Wednesday demanding compensation
for what they said looting of their houses following the emergency
evacuation, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
