<HEADLINE> Dry Nicaraguan City Declares Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan city of Matagalpa
declared a state of emergency on Tuesday because of a lack of
water.
</P>
<P>
The city, about 130 kilometers away from Managua, is suffering
the severe water shortage because of the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Jaime Castro Navarro, mayor of the city, has asked the central
government to send flushing cisterns to the city.
</P>
<P>
The mayor also asked the education minister to temporarily
close 12 schools to reduce the risk of an epidemic caused by lack
of water.
</P>
<P>
The city's 230,000 inhabitants get their water from the Molino
Norte and Grande Rivers of Matagalpa. But because of the dry
season, the two rivers do not have enough water to supply the
population.
</P>
<P>
The emergency state may be prolonged until the beginning of
June, when the rainy season arrives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
