<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Decides to Try Alleged Nazi Criminal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Federation Court
decided on Wednesday to bring to trial Dinko Sakich, an alleged
Nazi war criminal who hid in Argentina after the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made under the criminal law of the Yugoslav
Federation, a Yugoslav News Agency report said.
</P>
<P>
Sakich, who is now 76, was the commander in the Jasenovec Nazi
concentration camp in Yugoslavia during World War II. He is
claimed to have been responsible for the slaughter of 70,000
Serbians, Jews, Gypsies and Croatians.
</P>
<P>
He was declared a war criminal in 1947 by the former Yugoslav
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Sakich was found recently in Argentina and his whereabouts are
not known now.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav Federation Court instructed the Belgrade District
Court to hold the trial of Sakich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
