<HEADLINE> Russia Seeks "Transparency" in U.S.-Japan Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States-Japan military
relations should be "transparent" and limited to a defensive
nature, a Russian Foreign Ministry official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Rakhmanin, director of the Information and Press
Department, made the remark in response to reported support by the
Japanese government for U.S.-Japan military cooperation
legislation.
</P>
<P>
Russian media reports said that under the three bills backed by
Tokyo, U.S. forces could enjoy "logistic support" from the
Japanese forces "in case of emergency" in East Asian areas
extending from Russia's Sakhalin to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin said the Russian Foreign Ministry was closely
watching every move in U.S.-Japanese military relations, and it
was an important topic in Russia's dialogue with the U.S. and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Considering lessons of history, the characteristics of the
Asia-Pacific region and the new international political reality,
any change in U.S.-Japanese military cooperation should be
transparent and be strictly limited to a defensive nature, he
stressed. 
</P>
