<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Bans Logging of Precious Timber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 29 -- Nicaragua President Arnoldo Aleman signed
a decree on Wednesday to prevent logging of mahogany, cedar and
bombax trees throughout the national territory over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
"This not only benefits ourselves, but also future generations
of the whole world," said a statement releaseed by the government.
</P>
<P>
The decree says that the degradation rates in the country are
growing at an alarming pace, due mainly to timber exploitation, so
it is necessary to check and up-date the use and utilization of
the forests.
</P>
<P>
The decree will cancel all the logging permits of the three
timbers, and warns that any violation will resault in the
confiscation of the timber and fines of up to 20,000 cordobas
(around 2,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
President Aleman expressed the view that a sole decree would
not be enough to prohibit the logging of precious trees, and it
was urgent that "deputies enact a law imposing jail sanctions on
everybody who does not respect the resolution."
</P>
<P>
The decision of the Nicaraguan government has been taken
because of the constant denunciations of over-exploitation of
forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
On a recent trip, the comptroller general of the republic,
Agustin Jarquin, witnessed the condition of forestry exploitation
caused by the over-logging formerly granted by the ministry of
environment and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Last monday the comptroller sent a letter to the government
requesting urgent measures to protect the natural resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
