<HEADLINE> Deadline Extended for Expulsion of Illegal Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has decided
to extend the deadline for repatriating foreign illegal workers
for another 30 days.
</P>
<P>
However, the extension of the deadline, originally set for may
1, is only applied to foreign workers working at rice mills,
quarries and rubber plantations.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul, who chairs a national
committee to solve foreign labor problems, said on Wednesday that
the committee had agreed to give the employment department 30 more
days after may 1 to find if there was a shortage of labor in rice
mills, quarries and rubber plantations.
</P>
<P>
If the findings showed that there was not such a shortage as
stated by some businessmen, the foreign workers would be
repatriated, Bhichai was quoted by Thursday's Bangkok Post as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government said earlier that it would repatriate about
300,000 foreign workers this year. there are more than 1 million
foreign workers in Thailand, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Under the April 28 cabinet resolution, Myanmar, Cambodian and
Laotian workers are allowed to continue working in 13 border
provinces but cannot stay overnight in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
These people can also seek Thai authorities' permission to work
for the fisheries industry and other related industries in 22
provinces for another year.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 representatives from the rice mills association of
Thailand have asked the Thai government to ensure that concerned
officials refrain from taking any action against millers who
continue to employ foreigners after the may 1 deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
