<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Postal Dispute Takes New Turn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's postal dispute has
taken a new turn for the worse from today with workers deciding to
stage a sit down strike, postal union sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Workers in post offices throughout the country will stage a sit
down strike whereby they will report for duty but will not perform
any work, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the Union of Posts and Telecom Officers
N.P. Hettiarachchi said this was in addition to the overtime
boycott they were conducting at present.
</P>
<P>
This latest act of defiance was against the transfer of nine
union leaders.
</P>
<P>
The transfers followed the promulgation of Emergency
Regulations to declare the postal service an Essential Service by
the government last Friday to stifle a 44-day strike by the postal
Unions demanding overtime payments and the removal of the Post
Master General.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that a sit down strike by postal workers
would be a violation of the Essential Services promulgation and
they would be liable to punishment.
</P>
<P>
Measures by the government to mediate in the strike have so far
failed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile several trade unions outside the postal service both
in the state and private sectors are due to stage a massive lunch
hour demonstration in Colombo today against the governments
decision to use Emergency Regulations to stifle the strike and the
arrest of union leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
