<HEADLINE> Italy's Industrial Turnover, Orders Increase in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Italy's industrial turnover was up
6.1 percent in January 1998 over the same month in 1997, while
orders were up 10.6 percent, the national statistics bureau Istat
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Istat said that the turnover rise was boosted by both the
domestic market, with sales up 4.8 percent, and the foreign
market, with turnover up nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, domestic orders were up 11.3 percent and foreign
orders increased by 9.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The data confirmed a general upswing in the productive sector,
Istat said.
</P>
<P>
Its report showed that sales of investment goods were up 10.3
percent, intermediate products five percent and consumer goods 4.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
January figures revealed that the strongest gains had been made
in the metal industry (up 18.3 percent), the transport production
industry (up 16.3 percent), the electrical machine production
sector (up 12.7 percent) and the paper industry (up 11.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
On the down side, turnover in the oil industry fell 8.6 percent
and in the leather tanning industry 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
As for orders, the transport production sector was a clear
success with a huge 64 percent rise. Orders in the metal sector
rose 16.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
