<HEADLINE> U.S. Pleased with Contact Group Meeting on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Wednesday
expressed satisfaction with the outcome of a meeting of the
Contact Group on the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We think it was a constructive meeting," State Department
spokesman James Foley said after the six-nation Contact Group,
meeting in Rome, agreed on a response to Yugoslavia's handling of
ethnic tensions in its province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We're very pleased that the Contact Group by and large backed
the proposals advanced by the United States," said Foley. "We
think the package is a good one and it offers (Yugoslav President
Slobodan) Milosevic a stark choice."
</P>
<P>
A statement issued in Rome on Wednesday by officials of
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States
promised that if Belgrade eased tensions in Kosovo it would regain
its place in international organizations from which it has been
barred.
</P>
<P>
It imposed an immediate freeze on Yugoslav assets abroad and
threatened to stop new investment in Serbia by May 9 if Yugoslav
authorities did not start a dialogue with Kosovo's Albanian
majority.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Russia's failure to agree to the sanctions, Foley
said: "I think we weren't surprised at all." 
