<HEADLINE> IMF Satisfied With Indonesia's Reform Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Special envoy of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in Indonesia Prabhakar Narvekar
has expressed the Fund's satisfaction with the country's
performance in implementing its ongoing economic reform measures.
</P>
<P>
Narvekar made the expression here Wednesday after meeting with
Indonesian Vice President B.J. Habibie, the "Jakarta Post" daily
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF envoy said he was optimistic the IMF executive board
would agree to disburse its suspended credit outlay on time.
</P>
<P>
However, the final decision will be made by the 24-member board
which is to met on May 4, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and the IMF reached an agreement in October last year
on a 43 billion U.S. dollar bailout package to overcome the
country's monetary crisis. The Indonesian government promised to
conduct wide-ranging economic and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
The IMF disbursed the first tranche of 3 billion U.S. dollars
in aid in December.
</P>
<P>
But the IMF delayed the second tranche of 3 billion dollars
scheduled last month after Indonesia failed to implement key terms
of its agreement with IMF.
</P>
<P>
Under a revised program agreement reached earlier this month,
Indonesia is subject to monthly performance reviews instead of
quarterly review under the initial IMF program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
