<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contact Group Steps Up Pressure for End to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The six-nation Contact Group on the
former Yugoslavia has announced a package of "incentives and
deterrents" to push Yugoslavia and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo into
a negotiated end to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Rome on Wednesday, the six states -- the United
States, France, Britain, Russia, Italy and Germany -- called for
an immediate end to violence in the Serbian province and the
opening of dialogue between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Although the six delegations urged both sides to renounce all
conditions of dialogue, the agreed package of measures mainly
targeted the Yugoslav government of President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Among the incentives was the full reintegration of Yugoslavia
into international organizations, while the deterrents included a
freeze on Serbia's and the Yugoslav Federation's foreign assets --
a measure proposed at the Contact Group's meeting in London last
month.
</P>
<P>
The group also announced that if Belgrade hindered the start
of dialogue, the group's next meeting in Paris would call for a
halt on all foreign investments in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint declaration released after the meeting,
Russian representatives withheld approval for the two deterrents,
saying they were excessively "punitive."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Russian Foreign Ministry said that only the
United Nations Security Council had the right to impose sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's announcement appeared to coincide with the
U.S. calls this week for harsher sanctions against Yugoslavia,
which Washington believes has not been doing enough to halt the
violence. This position is generally shared in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Although Belgrade has offered to negotiate with the ethnic
Albanians, their leader Ibrahim Rugova has not taken up the offer,
claiming it is only a ploy to cover recent Serb military action in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo Albanians, who form 90 percent of the province's two
million population, want autonomy for their province while some
sections of the community there are calling for fully-fledged
secession.
</P>
<P>
So far Serbia has refused to consider the idea and Western
countries have also said secession is not an option, although a
greater level of self-rule is.
</P>
<P>
About 80 people have been killed in the province in the clashes
between the Serb police and alleged separatists since this
February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
