<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Students Train Redundant Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Jingxia, 49, who was declared
redundant by her factory three years ago, never dreamed that she
would one day have chances to continue her study at a university.
</P>
<P>
Now, the dream has become true. She was recently accepted by
the China Science and Technology University to attend the computer
training class.
</P>
<P>
The teachers of Zhou and some 40 other unemployeed workers in
Hefei, capital of east China's Anhui Province, are not professors
of this elite university but four university students.
</P>
<P>
The free training course, the first of its kind for unemployeed
workers, is taught by student volunteers from the university's
Fragrant Grass Society.
</P>
<P>
Since last July, the society has cooperated with the local
community headquarters to help the families of unemployeed and and
poor workers. Students have served as tutors for children from
related families and provide free first-aid services to
poverty-stricken residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
