<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Leaders Confident of Approving NATO's Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate leaders said on
Wednesday they were confident that the Senate will vote for NATO
expanding on tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Following their meeting with President Bill Clinton, both
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and Minority Leader Tom Daschle
said they believe the measure on the alliance's expansion will win
a two-thirds majority in the 100-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that we are going to be able to do that, and we
will have final passage tomorrow of this very important treaty
that is important to, I think not only the United States national
security but security in all of Europe," Lott told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Senate began the debate on Monday and has focused on more
than two dozens of amendments to the measure.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Lott and Daschle at the White House, Clinton
said, "I must say, I've been very impressed by the debate and I'm
looking forward to a positive vote by the end of this week."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Senate rejected by 62-37 one attempt to set
up a special NATO process to resolve disputes among allies but
more than dozens of amendments to the measure remained to be voted
on Thursday and final passage could slip to Friday.
</P>
<P>
The amendments, which only require a simple majority, include a
move by Democratic Sen. Daniel Moynihan of New York to allow
countries to join NATO only after they have been allowed into the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Senate also overwhelmingly rejected a measure
to limit the U.S. shares in the costs of expanding NATO.
</P>
<P>
The amendment proposed by Senator Tom Harkin would have
restricted the amount of military subsidies the United States
provides to the prospective members to 25 percent of total NATO
aid to the countries.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO signed accession protocols with Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic in December and the three countries
will be full NATO members after the documents are ratified by all
NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Canada, Denmark, Germany and Norway have ratified the protocols
up to date. A NATO summit meeting has been scheduled in
Washington next spring to formally accept the new three members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
