<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Destroys 120,000 Spindles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a leading
industrial base in northeast China, has significantly reduced its
textile production capacity by destroying 120,000 obsolete
spindles since the initial reduction project was completed by the
Shenyang Textile Mill on March 25.
</P>
<P>
Local sources indicate that the province plans to destroy over
691,000 obsolete cotton spindles over the next three years in a
move to reduce the province's total textile production capacity by
50 percent. Some 410,000 spindles will be destroyed this year, and
some 80,000 textile workers will lose their jobs over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning will not only carry out the spindle reduction
campaign, but will also establish six textile groups by
introducing inter-regional mergers among cotton mills.
</P>
<P>
The Shenyang Textile Mill, established over 70 years ago, will
remove 75,000 of its 88,000 spindles, and in turn significantly
reduce its payroll by laying off some 4,000 workers during 1998.
</P>
<P>
The mill will close down operations covering 100,000 sq.m, and
will introduce real estate development and property management
departments, in addition to forming a textile group based on
several local textile mills, according to company officials.
</P>
<P>
China launched a national spindle reduction campaign earlier
this year in a bid to raise the efficiency of the textile industry
and help related firms turn losses into profits.
</P>
<P>
The national plans call for the textile sector to destroy 10
million obsolete cotton spindles by the year 2000, in addition to
transferring some 1.2 million textile workers to other sectors.
</P>
<P>
China destroyed some 742,000 obsolete cotton spindles during
the first quarter of this year, or 98.9 percent of the targeted
figure for the period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980430.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Sees Moderate GDP Growth for Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has projected that
the gross domestic product (GDP) of the Philippines will post a
2.8 percent growth in 1998 despite the slowdown in business
activities due to the lingering effects of a depreciating
currency.
</P>
<P>
In a confidential country assessment report published here
Thursday, the bank said that a "sharp reduction in growth appears
unavoidable under current conditions of tightening credit
availability and its impact on private consumption and
investment."
</P>
<P>
The GDP projection is a big contraction from the 5.1-percent
growth for the overall 1997. But it is still higher than the lower
end of the range target of 2.4 percent programmed under the
International Monetary Fund (IMF)-backed precautionary
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
As the economy weathers the currency storm, the bank foresees
the domestic economy to rebound and post a growth of 4.8 percent
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, the World Bank said that the incoming administration
will have to adhere to the precautionary agreement set forth with
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The bank stressed that the conditionalities tied to the
18-month precautionary arrangement are designed to strengthen the
economy.
</P>
<P>
"We and the IMF aim to contain the remaining risks through a
number of safeguards including agreement on strong programs that
bind the current and new administration and provide framework for
continuity of policies," the bank declared.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the incoming presidential elections
would impact on the economic growth as there is uncertainty
whether the new administration would proceed with the structural
reform measures adopted by previous governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
