<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Olympic Competitors to Be Models </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Wednesday that American Olympians should become models for
young people.
</P>
<P>
"If you choose, for the rest of your lives, because you were an
Olympian, you can have a profound, positive impact on all the
people with whom you come in contact, but especially on young
people," said Clinton in meeting athletes who participated in the
1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, on the White House South
Lawn.
</P>
<P>
"The lessons of setting your sights high, working hard, being
persistent, believing in yourselves, playing by the rules,
supporting your team, those are lessons that every child in
America needs to learn -- lessons that every child can see in your
eyes and in the power of your example," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Michelle Kwan, 1998 Olympic silver medalist and World Figure
Skating Championship gold medalist, presented to Clinton an
Olympic USA team warmup jacket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
