<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Pledges to Promote Closer EU-GCC Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here Wednesday that the European Union (EU) countries
would promote cooperation with six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
countries in the future.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ministerial meeting of EU and GCC countries held
here Wednesday, Cook, whose country is the EU president, said:
"One of our highest priorities during our presidency of the
European Union was to enhance the political exchanges between the
EU and our partners in the Gulf."
</P>
<P>
"Recent regional crises have underlined the need for close
dialogue. The stability and prosperity of the Gulf are vital for
the EU. We need to work in partnership to promote regional
security," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
On the Iraqi situation, Cook said that the EU and GCC countries
"are united in insisting that Iraq fulfils the obligations laid
down by the UN."
</P>
<P>
"We will not weaken in our resolve. We must continue to work
together to ensure that Saddam Hussein (Iraqi President) is not
allowed to ignore the wishes of the international community," Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Cook said that 15-nation
European bloc and the GCC countries "can find practical ways to
move the (Middle East) peace process forward."
</P>
<P>
The EU side is represented by Britain, Luxembourg and Austria
while the GCC comprises Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, the
United Arab Emirates and Oman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
